1|"THE PRINCE"|FALSE
1|"by Nicolo Machiavelli"|FALSE
1|"Translated by W. K. Marriott"|FALSE
1|"Nicolo Machiavelli, born at Florence on 3rd May 1469. From 1494 to 1512"|FALSE
1|"held an official post at Florence which included diplomatic missions to"|FALSE
1|"various European courts. Imprisoned in Florence, 1512; later exiled and"|FALSE
1|"returned to San Casciano. Died at Florence on 22nd June 1527."|FALSE
1|"INTRODUCTION"|FALSE
1|"Nicolo Machiavelli was born at Florence on 3rd May 1469. He was the"|FALSE
1|"second son of Bernardo di Nicolo Machiavelli, a lawyer of some repute,"|FALSE
1|"and of Bartolommea di Stefano Nelli, his wife. Both parents were members"|FALSE
1|"of the old Florentine nobility."|FALSE
1|"His life falls naturally into three periods, each of which singularly"|FALSE
1|"enough constitutes a distinct and important era in the history of"|FALSE
1|"Florence. His youth was concurrent with the greatness of Florence as an"|FALSE
1|"Italian power under the guidance of Lorenzo de' Medici, Il Magnifico."|FALSE
1|"The downfall of the Medici in Florence occurred in 1494, in which year"|FALSE
1|"Machiavelli entered the public service. During his official career"|FALSE
1|"Florence was free under the government of a Republic, which lasted"|FALSE
1|"until 1512, when the Medici returned to power, and Machiavelli lost his"|FALSE
1|"office. The Medici again ruled Florence from 1512 until 1527, when they"|FALSE
1|"were once more driven out. This was the period of Machiavelli's literary"|FALSE
1|"activity and increasing influence; but he died, within a few weeks of"|FALSE
1|"the expulsion of the Medici, on 22nd June 1527, in his fifty-eighth"|FALSE
1|"year, without having regained office."|FALSE
1|"YOUTH -- Aet. 1-25--1469-94"|FALSE
1|"Although there is little recorded of the youth of Machiavelli, the"|FALSE
1|"Florence of those days is so well known that the early environment of"|FALSE
1|"this representative citizen may be easily imagined. Florence has been"|FALSE
1|"described as a city with two opposite currents of life, one directed by"|FALSE
1|"the fervent and austere Savonarola, the other by the splendour-loving"|FALSE
1|"Lorenzo. Savonarola's influence upon the young Machiavelli must have"|FALSE
1|"been slight, for although at one time he wielded immense power over the"|FALSE
1|"fortunes of Florence, he only furnished Machiavelli with a subject of"|FALSE
1|"a gibe in \"The Prince,\" where he is cited as an example of an unarmed"|FALSE
1|"prophet who came to a bad end. Whereas the magnificence of the Medicean"|FALSE
1|"rule during the life of Lorenzo appeared to have impressed Machiavelli"|FALSE
1|"strongly, for he frequently recurs to it in his writings, and it is to"|FALSE
1|"Lorenzo's grandson that he dedicates \"The Prince.\""|FALSE
1|"Machiavelli, in his \"History of Florence,\" gives us a picture of the"|FALSE
1|"young men among whom his youth was passed. He writes: \"They were freer"|FALSE
1|"than their forefathers in dress and living, and spent more in other"|FALSE
1|"kinds of excesses, consuming their time and money in idleness, gaming,"|FALSE
1|"and women; their chief aim was to appear well dressed and to speak with"|FALSE
1|"wit and acuteness, whilst he who could wound others the most cleverly"|FALSE
1|"was thought the wisest.\" In a letter to his son Guido, Machiavelli shows"|FALSE
1|"why youth should avail itself of its opportunities for study, and leads"|FALSE
1|"us to infer that his own youth had been so occupied. He writes: \"I"|FALSE
1|"have received your letter, which has given me the greatest pleasure,"|FALSE
1|"especially because you tell me you are quite restored in health, than"|FALSE
1|"which I could have no better news; for if God grant life to you, and"|FALSE
1|"to me, I hope to make a good man of you if you are willing to do your"|FALSE
1|"share.\" Then, writing of a new patron, he continues: \"This will turn"|FALSE
1|"out well for you, but it is necessary for you to study; since, then, you"|FALSE
1|"have no longer the excuse of illness, take pains to study letters and"|FALSE
1|"music, for you see what honour is done to me for the little skill I"|FALSE
1|"have. Therefore, my son, if you wish to please me, and to bring success"|FALSE
1|"and honour to yourself, do right and study, because others will help you"|FALSE
1|"if you help yourself.\""|FALSE
1|"OFFICE -- Aet. 25-43--1494-1512"|FALSE
1|"The second period of Machiavelli's life was spent in the service of the"|FALSE
1|"free Republic of Florence, which flourished, as stated above, from"|FALSE
1|"the expulsion of the Medici in 1494 until their return in 1512. After"|FALSE
1|"serving four years in one of the public offices he was appointed"|FALSE
1|"Chancellor and Secretary to the Second Chancery, the Ten of Liberty"|FALSE
1|"and Peace. Here we are on firm ground when dealing with the events of"|FALSE
1|"Machiavelli's life, for during this time he took a leading part in"|FALSE
1|"the affairs of the Republic, and we have its decrees, records,"|FALSE
1|"and dispatches to guide us, as well as his own writings. A mere"|FALSE
1|"recapitulation of a few of his transactions with the statesmen and"|FALSE
1|"soldiers of his time gives a fair indication of his activities, and"|FALSE
1|"supplies the sources from which he drew the experiences and characters"|FALSE
1|"which illustrate \"The Prince.\""|FALSE
1|"His first mission was in 1499 to Catherina Sforza, \"my lady of Forli\" of"|FALSE
1|"\"The Prince,\" from whose conduct and fate he drew the moral that it"|FALSE
1|"is far better to earn the confidence of the people than to rely on"|FALSE
1|"fortresses. This is a very noticeable principle in Machiavelli, and is"|FALSE
1|"urged by him in many ways as a matter of vital importance to princes."|FALSE
1|"In 1500 he was sent to France to obtain terms from Louis XII for"|FALSE
1|"continuing the war against Pisa: this king it was who, in his conduct"|FALSE
1|"of affairs in Italy, committed the five capital errors in statecraft"|FALSE
1|"summarized in \"The Prince,\" and was consequently driven out. He, also,"|FALSE
1|"it was who made the dissolution of his marriage a condition of support"|FALSE
1|"to Pope Alexander VI; which leads Machiavelli to refer those who urge"|FALSE
1|"that such promises should be kept to what he has written concerning the"|FALSE
1|"faith of princes."|FALSE
1|"Machiavelli's public life was largely occupied with events arising out"|FALSE
1|"of the ambitions of Pope Alexander VI and his son, Cesare Borgia, the"|FALSE
1|"Duke Valentino, and these characters fill a large space of \"The Prince.\""|FALSE
1|"Machiavelli never hesitates to cite the actions of the duke for the"|FALSE
1|"benefit of usurpers who wish to keep the states they have seized; he"|FALSE
1|"can, indeed, find no precepts to offer so good as the pattern of Cesare"|FALSE
1|"Borgia's conduct, insomuch that Cesare is acclaimed by some critics as"|FALSE
1|"the \"hero\" of \"The Prince.\" Yet in \"The Prince\" the duke is in point of"|FALSE
1|"fact cited as a type of the man who rises on the fortune of others, and"|FALSE
1|"falls with them; who takes every course that might be expected from a"|FALSE
1|"prudent man but the course which will save him; who is prepared for all"|FALSE
1|"eventualities but the one which happens; and who, when all his abilities"|FALSE
1|"fail to carry him through, exclaims that it was not his fault, but an"|FALSE
1|"extraordinary and unforeseen fatality."|FALSE
1|"On the death of Pius III, in 1503, Machiavelli was sent to Rome to watch"|FALSE
1|"the election of his successor, and there he saw Cesare Borgia cheated"|FALSE
1|"into allowing the choice of the College to fall on Giuliano delle Rovere"|FALSE
1|"(Julius II), who was one of the cardinals that had most reason to fear"|FALSE
1|"the duke. Machiavelli, when commenting on this election, says that"|FALSE
1|"he who thinks new favours will cause great personages to forget old"|FALSE
1|"injuries deceives himself. Julius did not rest until he had ruined"|FALSE
1|"Cesare."|FALSE
1|"It was to Julius II that Machiavelli was sent in 1506, when that pontiff"|FALSE
1|"was commencing his enterprise against Bologna; which he brought to a"|FALSE
1|"successful issue, as he did many of his other adventures, owing chiefly"|FALSE
1|"to his impetuous character. It is in reference to Pope Julius that"|FALSE
1|"Machiavelli moralizes on the resemblance between Fortune and women, and"|FALSE
1|"concludes that it is the bold rather than the cautious man that will win"|FALSE
1|"and hold them both."|FALSE
1|"It is impossible to follow here the varying fortunes of the Italian"|FALSE
1|"states, which in 1507 were controlled by France, Spain, and Germany,"|FALSE
1|"with results that have lasted to our day; we are concerned with those"|FALSE
1|"events, and with the three great actors in them, so far only as they"|FALSE
1|"impinge on the personality of Machiavelli. He had several meetings with"|FALSE
1|"Louis XII of France, and his estimate of that monarch's character has"|FALSE
1|"already been alluded to. Machiavelli has painted Ferdinand of Aragon as"|FALSE
1|"the man who accomplished great things under the cloak of religion, but"|FALSE
1|"who in reality had no mercy, faith, humanity, or integrity; and who,"|FALSE
1|"had he allowed himself to be influenced by such motives, would have been"|FALSE
1|"ruined. The Emperor Maximilian was one of the most interesting men"|FALSE
1|"of the age, and his character has been drawn by many hands; but"|FALSE
1|"Machiavelli, who was an envoy at his court in 1507-8, reveals the secret"|FALSE
1|"of his many failures when he describes him as a secretive man, without"|FALSE
1|"force of character--ignoring the human agencies necessary to carry"|FALSE
1|"his schemes into effect, and never insisting on the fulfilment of his"|FALSE
1|"wishes."|FALSE
1|"The remaining years of Machiavelli's official career were filled with"|FALSE
1|"events arising out of the League of Cambrai, made in 1508 between the"|FALSE
1|"three great European powers already mentioned and the pope, with the"|FALSE
1|"object of crushing the Venetian Republic. This result was attained in"|FALSE
1|"the battle of Vaila, when Venice lost in one day all that she had won in"|FALSE
1|"eight hundred years. Florence had a difficult part to play during these"|FALSE
1|"events, complicated as they were by the feud which broke out between"|FALSE
1|"the pope and the French, because friendship with France had dictated the"|FALSE
1|"entire policy of the Republic. When, in 1511, Julius II finally formed"|FALSE
1|"the Holy League against France, and with the assistance of the Swiss"|FALSE
1|"drove the French out of Italy, Florence lay at the mercy of the Pope,"|FALSE
1|"and had to submit to his terms, one of which was that the Medici should"|FALSE
1|"be restored. The return of the Medici to Florence on 1st September"|FALSE
1|"1512, and the consequent fall of the Republic, was the signal for the"|FALSE
1|"dismissal of Machiavelli and his friends, and thus put an end to his"|FALSE
1|"public career, for, as we have seen, he died without regaining office."|FALSE
1|"LITERATURE AND DEATH -- Aet. 43-58--1512-27"|FALSE
1|"On the return of the Medici, Machiavelli, who for a few weeks had"|FALSE
1|"vainly hoped to retain his office under the new masters of Florence, was"|FALSE
1|"dismissed by decree dated 7th November 1512. Shortly after this he was"|FALSE
1|"accused of complicity in an abortive conspiracy against the Medici,"|FALSE
1|"imprisoned, and put to the question by torture. The new Medicean pope,"|FALSE
1|"Leo X, procured his release, and he retired to his small property at San"|FALSE
1|"Casciano, near Florence, where he devoted himself to literature. In a"|FALSE
1|"letter to Francesco Vettori, dated 13th December 1513, he has left"|FALSE
1|"a very interesting description of his life at this period, which"|FALSE
1|"elucidates his methods and his motives in writing \"The Prince.\" After"|FALSE
1|"describing his daily occupations with his family and neighbours, he"|FALSE
1|"writes: \"The evening being come, I return home and go to my study; at"|FALSE
1|"the entrance I pull off my peasant-clothes, covered with dust and dirt,"|FALSE
1|"and put on my noble court dress, and thus becomingly re-clothed I"|FALSE
1|"pass into the ancient courts of the men of old, where, being lovingly"|FALSE
1|"received by them, I am fed with that food which is mine alone; where I"|FALSE
1|"do not hesitate to speak with them, and to ask for the reason of their"|FALSE
1|"actions, and they in their benignity answer me; and for four hours I"|FALSE
1|"feel no weariness, I forget every trouble, poverty does not dismay,"|FALSE
1|"death does not terrify me; I am possessed entirely by those great men."|FALSE
1|"And because Dante says:"|FALSE
1|"     Knowledge doth come of learning well retained,"|FALSE
1|"     Unfruitful else,"|FALSE
1|"I have noted down what I have gained from their conversation, and have"|FALSE
1|"composed a small work on 'Principalities,' where I pour myself out"|FALSE
1|"as fully as I can in meditation on the subject, discussing what a"|FALSE
1|"principality is, what kinds there are, how they can be acquired, how"|FALSE
1|"they can be kept, why they are lost: and if any of my fancies ever"|FALSE
1|"pleased you, this ought not to displease you: and to a prince,"|FALSE
1|"especially to a new one, it should be welcome: therefore I dedicate it"|FALSE
1|"to his Magnificence Giuliano. Filippo Casavecchio has seen it; he will"|FALSE
1|"be able to tell you what is in it, and of the discourses I have had with"|FALSE
1|"him; nevertheless, I am still enriching and polishing it.\""|FALSE
1|"The \"little book\" suffered many vicissitudes before attaining the form"|FALSE
1|"in which it has reached us. Various mental influences were at work"|FALSE
1|"during its composition; its title and patron were changed; and for some"|FALSE
1|"unknown reason it was finally dedicated to Lorenzo de' Medici. Although"|FALSE
1|"Machiavelli discussed with Casavecchio whether it should be sent or"|FALSE
1|"presented in person to the patron, there is no evidence that Lorenzo"|FALSE
1|"ever received or even read it: he certainly never gave Machiavelli any"|FALSE
1|"employment. Although it was plagiarized during Machiavelli's lifetime,"|FALSE
1|"\"The Prince\" was never published by him, and its text is still"|FALSE
1|"disputable."|FALSE
1|"Machiavelli concludes his letter to Vettori thus: \"And as to this little"|FALSE
1|"thing [his book], when it has been read it will be seen that during the"|FALSE
1|"fifteen years I have given to the study of statecraft I have neither"|FALSE
1|"slept nor idled; and men ought ever to desire to be served by one who"|FALSE
1|"has reaped experience at the expense of others. And of my loyalty none"|FALSE
1|"could doubt, because having always kept faith I could not now learn how"|FALSE
1|"to break it; for he who has been faithful and honest, as I have, cannot"|FALSE
1|"change his nature; and my poverty is a witness to my honesty.\""|FALSE
1|"Before Machiavelli had got \"The Prince\" off his hands he commenced his"|FALSE
1|"\"Discourse on the First Decade of Titus Livius,\" which should be read"|FALSE
1|"concurrently with \"The Prince.\" These and several minor works occupied"|FALSE
1|"him until the year 1518, when he accepted a small commission to look"|FALSE
1|"after the affairs of some Florentine merchants at Genoa. In 1519 the"|FALSE
1|"Medicean rulers of Florence granted a few political concessions to"|FALSE
1|"her citizens, and Machiavelli with others was consulted upon a new"|FALSE
1|"constitution under which the Great Council was to be restored; but on"|FALSE
1|"one pretext or another it was not promulgated."|FALSE
1|"In 1520 the Florentine merchants again had recourse to Machiavelli"|FALSE
1|"to settle their difficulties with Lucca, but this year was chiefly"|FALSE
1|"remarkable for his re-entry into Florentine literary society, where he"|FALSE
1|"was much sought after, and also for the production of his \"Art of War.\""|FALSE
1|"It was in the same year that he received a commission at the instance"|FALSE
1|"of Cardinal de' Medici to write the \"History of Florence,\" a task"|FALSE
1|"which occupied him until 1525. His return to popular favour may have"|FALSE
1|"determined the Medici to give him this employment, for an old writer"|FALSE
1|"observes that \"an able statesman out of work, like a huge whale, will"|FALSE
1|"endeavour to overturn the ship unless he has an empty cask to play"|FALSE
1|"with.\""|FALSE
1|"When the \"History of Florence\" was finished, Machiavelli took it to"|FALSE
1|"Rome for presentation to his patron, Giuliano de' Medici, who had in"|FALSE
1|"the meanwhile become pope under the title of Clement VII. It is somewhat"|FALSE
1|"remarkable that, as, in 1513, Machiavelli had written \"The Prince\" for"|FALSE
1|"the instruction of the Medici after they had just regained power in"|FALSE
1|"Florence, so, in 1525, he dedicated the \"History of Florence\" to the"|FALSE
1|"head of the family when its ruin was now at hand. In that year the"|FALSE
1|"battle of Pavia destroyed the French rule in Italy, and left Francis I"|FALSE
1|"a prisoner in the hands of his great rival, Charles V. This was followed"|FALSE
1|"by the sack of Rome, upon the news of which the popular party at"|FALSE
1|"Florence threw off the yoke of the Medici, who were once more banished."|FALSE
1|"Machiavelli was absent from Florence at this time, but hastened his"|FALSE
1|"return, hoping to secure his former office of secretary to the \"Ten of"|FALSE
1|"Liberty and Peace.\" Unhappily he was taken ill soon after he reached"|FALSE
1|"Florence, where he died on 22nd June 1527."|FALSE
1|"THE MAN AND HIS WORKS"|FALSE
1|"No one can say where the bones of Machiavelli rest, but modern Florence"|FALSE
1|"has decreed him a stately cenotaph in Santa Croce, by the side of her"|FALSE
1|"most famous sons; recognizing that, whatever other nations may have"|FALSE
1|"found in his works, Italy found in them the idea of her unity and the"|FALSE
1|"germs of her renaissance among the nations of Europe. Whilst it is idle"|FALSE
1|"to protest against the world-wide and evil signification of his name,"|FALSE
1|"it may be pointed out that the harsh construction of his doctrine which"|FALSE
1|"this sinister reputation implies was unknown to his own day, and that"|FALSE
1|"the researches of recent times have enabled us to interpret him more"|FALSE
1|"reasonably. It is due to these inquiries that the shape of an \"unholy"|FALSE
1|"necromancer,\" which so long haunted men's vision, has begun to fade."|FALSE
1|"Machiavelli was undoubtedly a man of great observation, acuteness, and"|FALSE
1|"industry; noting with appreciative eye whatever passed before him, and"|FALSE
1|"with his supreme literary gift turning it to account in his enforced"|FALSE
1|"retirement from affairs. He does not present himself, nor is he"|FALSE
1|"depicted by his contemporaries, as a type of that rare combination,"|FALSE
1|"the successful statesman and author, for he appears to have been"|FALSE
1|"only moderately prosperous in his several embassies and political"|FALSE
1|"employments. He was misled by Catherina Sforza, ignored by Louis XII,"|FALSE
1|"overawed by Cesare Borgia; several of his embassies were quite barren of"|FALSE
1|"results; his attempts to fortify Florence failed, and the soldiery that"|FALSE
1|"he raised astonished everybody by their cowardice. In the conduct of his"|FALSE
1|"own affairs he was timid and time-serving; he dared not appear by the"|FALSE
1|"side of Soderini, to whom he owed so much, for fear of compromising"|FALSE
1|"himself; his connection with the Medici was open to suspicion, and"|FALSE
1|"Giuliano appears to have recognized his real forte when he set him to"|FALSE
1|"write the \"History of Florence,\" rather than employ him in the state."|FALSE
1|"And it is on the literary side of his character, and there alone, that"|FALSE
1|"we find no weakness and no failure."|FALSE
1|"Although the light of almost four centuries has been focused on \"The"|FALSE
1|"Prince,\" its problems are still debatable and interesting, because they"|FALSE
1|"are the eternal problems between the ruled and their rulers. Such as"|FALSE
1|"they are, its ethics are those of Machiavelli's contemporaries; yet they"|FALSE
1|"cannot be said to be out of date so long as the governments of Europe"|FALSE
1|"rely on material rather than on moral forces. Its historical incidents"|FALSE
1|"and personages become interesting by reason of the uses which"|FALSE
1|"Machiavelli makes of them to illustrate his theories of government and"|FALSE
1|"conduct."|FALSE
1|"Leaving out of consideration those maxims of state which still furnish"|FALSE
1|"some European and eastern statesmen with principles of action, \"The"|FALSE
1|"Prince\" is bestrewn with truths that can be proved at every turn. Men"|FALSE
1|"are still the dupes of their simplicity and greed, as they were in the"|FALSE
1|"days of Alexander VI. The cloak of religion still conceals the vices"|FALSE
1|"which Machiavelli laid bare in the character of Ferdinand of Aragon."|FALSE
1|"Men will not look at things as they really are, but as they wish them"|FALSE
1|"to be--and are ruined. In politics there are no perfectly safe courses;"|FALSE
1|"prudence consists in choosing the least dangerous ones. Then--to pass to"|FALSE
1|"a higher plane--Machiavelli reiterates that, although crimes may win"|FALSE
1|"an empire, they do not win glory. Necessary wars are just wars, and"|FALSE
1|"the arms of a nation are hallowed when it has no other resource but to"|FALSE
1|"fight."|FALSE
1|"It is the cry of a far later day than Machiavelli's that government"|FALSE
1|"should be elevated into a living moral force, capable of inspiring the"|FALSE
1|"people with a just recognition of the fundamental principles of society;"|FALSE
1|"to this \"high argument\" \"The Prince\" contributes but little. Machiavelli"|FALSE
1|"always refused to write either of men or of governments otherwise than"|FALSE
1|"as he found them, and he writes with such skill and insight that his"|FALSE
1|"work is of abiding value. But what invests \"The Prince\" with more than"|FALSE
1|"a merely artistic or historical interest is the incontrovertible truth"|FALSE
1|"that it deals with the great principles which still guide nations and"|FALSE
1|"rulers in their relationship with each other and their neighbours."|FALSE
1|"In translating \"The Prince\" my aim has been to achieve at all costs an"|FALSE
1|"exact literal rendering of the original, rather than a fluent paraphrase"|FALSE
1|"adapted to the modern notions of style and expression. Machiavelli was"|FALSE
1|"no facile phrasemonger; the conditions under which he wrote obliged him"|FALSE
1|"to weigh every word; his themes were lofty, his substance grave, his"|FALSE
1|"manner nobly plain and serious. \"Quis eo fuit unquam in partiundis"|FALSE
1|"rebus, in definiendis, in explanandis pressior?\" In \"The Prince,\" it may"|FALSE
1|"be truly said, there is reason assignable, not only for every word, but"|FALSE
1|"for the position of every word. To an Englishman of Shakespeare's time"|FALSE
1|"the translation of such a treatise was in some ways a comparatively easy"|FALSE
1|"task, for in those times the genius of the English more nearly resembled"|FALSE
1|"that of the Italian language; to the Englishman of to-day it is not so"|FALSE
1|"simple. To take a single example: the word \"intrattenere,\" employed by"|FALSE
1|"Machiavelli to indicate the policy adopted by the Roman Senate towards"|FALSE
1|"the weaker states of Greece, would by an Elizabethan be correctly"|FALSE
1|"rendered \"entertain,\" and every contemporary reader would understand"|FALSE
1|"what was meant by saying that \"Rome entertained the Aetolians and the"|FALSE
1|"Achaeans without augmenting their power.\" But to-day such a phrase would"|FALSE
1|"seem obsolete and ambiguous, if not unmeaning: we are compelled to say"|FALSE
1|"that \"Rome maintained friendly relations with the Aetolians,\" etc.,"|FALSE
1|"using four words to do the work of one. I have tried to preserve the"|FALSE
1|"pithy brevity of the Italian so far as was consistent with an absolute"|FALSE
1|"fidelity to the sense. If the result be an occasional asperity I can"|FALSE
1|"only hope that the reader, in his eagerness to reach the author's"|FALSE
1|"meaning, may overlook the roughness of the road that leads him to it."|FALSE
