1|"DEDICATION"|FALSE
1|"     To the Magnificent Lorenzo Di Piero De' Medici:"|FALSE
1|"     Those who strive to obtain the good graces of a prince are"|FALSE
1|"     accustomed to come before him with such things as they hold most"|FALSE
1|"     precious, or in which they see him take most delight; whence one"|FALSE
1|"     often sees horses, arms, cloth of gold, precious stones, and"|FALSE
1|"     similar ornaments presented to princes, worthy of their greatness."|FALSE
1|"     Desiring therefore to present myself to your Magnificence with"|FALSE
1|"     some testimony of my devotion towards you, I have not found among"|FALSE
1|"     my possessions anything which I hold more dear than, or value so"|FALSE
1|"     much as, the knowledge of the actions of great men, acquired by"|FALSE
1|"     long experience in contemporary affairs, and a continual study of"|FALSE
1|"     antiquity; which, having reflected upon it with great and"|FALSE
1|"     prolonged diligence, I now send, digested into a little volume, to"|FALSE
1|"     your Magnificence."|FALSE
1|"     And although I may consider this work unworthy of your"|FALSE
1|"     countenance, nevertheless I trust much to your benignity that it"|FALSE
1|"     may be acceptable, seeing that it is not possible for me to make a"|FALSE
1|"     better gift than to offer you the opportunity of understanding in"|FALSE
1|"     the shortest time all that I have learnt in so many years, and"|FALSE
1|"     with so many troubles and dangers; which work I have not"|FALSE
1|"     embellished with swelling or magnificent words, nor stuffed with"|FALSE
1|"     rounded periods, nor with any extrinsic allurements or adornments"|FALSE
1|"     whatever, with which so many are accustomed to embellish their"|FALSE
1|"     works; for I have wished either that no honour should be given it,"|FALSE
1|"     or else that the truth of the matter and the weightiness of the"|FALSE
1|"     theme shall make it acceptable."|FALSE
1|"     Nor do I hold with those who regard it as a presumption if a man"|FALSE
1|"     of low and humble condition dare to discuss and settle the"|FALSE
1|"     concerns of princes; because, just as those who draw landscapes"|FALSE
1|"     place themselves below in the plain to contemplate the nature of"|FALSE
1|"     the mountains and of lofty places, and in order to contemplate the"|FALSE
1|"     plains place themselves upon high mountains, even so to understand"|FALSE
1|"     the nature of the people it needs to be a prince, and to"|FALSE
1|"     understand that of princes it needs to be of the people."|FALSE
1|"     Take then, your Magnificence, this little gift in the spirit in"|FALSE
1|"     which I send it; wherein, if it be diligently read and considered"|FALSE
1|"     by you, you will learn my extreme desire that you should attain"|FALSE
1|"     that greatness which fortune and your other attributes promise."|FALSE
1|"     And if your Magnificence from the summit of your greatness will"|FALSE
1|"     sometimes turn your eyes to these lower regions, you will see how"|FALSE
1|"     unmeritedly I suffer a great and continued malignity of fortune."|FALSE
1|"THE PRINCE"|FALSE
1|"CHAPTER I -- HOW MANY KINDS OF PRINCIPALITIES THERE ARE, AND BY WHAT"|FALSE
1|"MEANS THEY ARE ACQUIRED"|FALSE
1|"All states, all powers, that have held and hold rule over men have been"|FALSE
1|"and are either republics or principalities."|FALSE
1|"Principalities are either hereditary, in which the family has been long"|FALSE
1|"established; or they are new."|FALSE
1|"The new are either entirely new, as was Milan to Francesco Sforza, or"|FALSE
1|"they are, as it were, members annexed to the hereditary state of the"|FALSE
1|"prince who has acquired them, as was the kingdom of Naples to that of"|FALSE
1|"the King of Spain."|FALSE
1|"Such dominions thus acquired are either accustomed to live under a"|FALSE
1|"prince, or to live in freedom; and are acquired either by the arms of"|FALSE
1|"the prince himself, or of others, or else by fortune or by ability."|FALSE
1|"CHAPTER II -- CONCERNING HEREDITARY PRINCIPALITIES"|FALSE
1|"I will leave out all discussion on republics, inasmuch as in another"|FALSE
1|"place I have written of them at length, and will address myself only to"|FALSE
1|"principalities. In doing so I will keep to the order indicated above,"|FALSE
1|"and discuss how such principalities are to be ruled and preserved."|FALSE
1|"I say at once there are fewer difficulties in holding hereditary states,"|FALSE
1|"and those long accustomed to the family of their prince, than new"|FALSE
1|"ones; for it is sufficient only not to transgress the customs of his"|FALSE
1|"ancestors, and to deal prudently with circumstances as they arise, for a"|FALSE
1|"prince of average powers to maintain himself in his state, unless he"|FALSE
1|"be deprived of it by some extraordinary and excessive force; and if he"|FALSE
1|"should be so deprived of it, whenever anything sinister happens to the"|FALSE
1|"usurper, he will regain it."|FALSE
1|"We have in Italy, for example, the Duke of Ferrara, who could not have"|FALSE
1|"withstood the attacks of the Venetians in '84, nor those of Pope Julius"|FALSE
1|"in '10, unless he had been long established in his dominions. For the"|FALSE
1|"hereditary prince has less cause and less necessity to offend; hence it"|FALSE
1|"happens that he will be more loved; and unless extraordinary vices cause"|FALSE
1|"him to be hated, it is reasonable to expect that his subjects will be"|FALSE
1|"naturally well disposed towards him; and in the antiquity and duration"|FALSE
1|"of his rule the memories and motives that make for change are lost, for"|FALSE
1|"one change always leaves the toothing for another."|FALSE
1|"CHAPTER III -- CONCERNING MIXED PRINCIPALITIES"|FALSE
1|"But the difficulties occur in a new principality. And firstly, if it be"|FALSE
1|"not entirely new, but is, as it were, a member of a state which, taken"|FALSE
1|"collectively, may be called composite, the changes arise chiefly from"|FALSE
1|"an inherent difficulty which there is in all new principalities; for"|FALSE
1|"men change their rulers willingly, hoping to better themselves, and this"|FALSE
1|"hope induces them to take up arms against him who rules: wherein they"|FALSE
1|"are deceived, because they afterwards find by experience they have"|FALSE
1|"gone from bad to worse. This follows also on another natural and common"|FALSE
1|"necessity, which always causes a new prince to burden those who have"|FALSE
1|"submitted to him with his soldiery and with infinite other hardships"|FALSE
1|"which he must put upon his new acquisition."|FALSE
1|"In this way you have enemies in all those whom you have injured in"|FALSE
1|"seizing that principality, and you are not able to keep those friends"|FALSE
1|"who put you there because of your not being able to satisfy them in the"|FALSE
1|"way they expected, and you cannot take strong measures against them,"|FALSE
1|"feeling bound to them. For, although one may be very strong in armed"|FALSE
1|"forces, yet in entering a province one has always need of the goodwill"|FALSE
1|"of the natives."|FALSE
1|"For these reasons Louis the Twelfth, King of France, quickly occupied"|FALSE
1|"Milan, and as quickly lost it; and to turn him out the first time it"|FALSE
1|"only needed Lodovico's own forces; because those who had opened the"|FALSE
1|"gates to him, finding themselves deceived in their hopes of future"|FALSE
1|"benefit, would not endure the ill-treatment of the new prince. It is"|FALSE
1|"very true that, after acquiring rebellious provinces a second time,"|FALSE
1|"they are not so lightly lost afterwards, because the prince, with"|FALSE
1|"little reluctance, takes the opportunity of the rebellion to punish the"|FALSE
1|"delinquents, to clear out the suspects, and to strengthen himself in the"|FALSE
1|"weakest places. Thus to cause France to lose Milan the first time it was"|FALSE
1|"enough for the Duke Lodovico(*) to raise insurrections on the borders;"|FALSE
1|"but to cause him to lose it a second time it was necessary to bring"|FALSE
1|"the whole world against him, and that his armies should be defeated and"|FALSE
1|"driven out of Italy; which followed from the causes above mentioned."|FALSE
1|"     (*) Duke Lodovico was Lodovico Moro, a son of Francesco"|FALSE
1|"     Sforza, who married Beatrice d'Este. He ruled over Milan"|FALSE
1|"     from 1494 to 1500, and died in 1510."|FALSE
1|"Nevertheless Milan was taken from France both the first and the second"|FALSE
1|"time. The general reasons for the first have been discussed; it remains"|FALSE
1|"to name those for the second, and to see what resources he had, and what"|FALSE
1|"any one in his situation would have had for maintaining himself more"|FALSE
1|"securely in his acquisition than did the King of France."|FALSE
1|"Now I say that those dominions which, when acquired, are added to an"|FALSE
1|"ancient state by him who acquires them, are either of the same country"|FALSE
1|"and language, or they are not. When they are, it is easier to hold them,"|FALSE
1|"especially when they have not been accustomed to self-government; and"|FALSE
1|"to hold them securely it is enough to have destroyed the family of the"|FALSE
1|"prince who was ruling them; because the two peoples, preserving in other"|FALSE
1|"things the old conditions, and not being unlike in customs, will live"|FALSE
1|"quietly together, as one has seen in Brittany, Burgundy, Gascony, and"|FALSE
1|"Normandy, which have been bound to France for so long a time: and,"|FALSE
1|"although there may be some difference in language, nevertheless the"|FALSE
1|"customs are alike, and the people will easily be able to get on amongst"|FALSE
1|"themselves. He who has annexed them, if he wishes to hold them, has only"|FALSE
1|"to bear in mind two considerations: the one, that the family of their"|FALSE
1|"former lord is extinguished; the other, that neither their laws nor"|FALSE
1|"their taxes are altered, so that in a very short time they will become"|FALSE
1|"entirely one body with the old principality."|FALSE
1|"But when states are acquired in a country differing in language,"|FALSE
1|"customs, or laws, there are difficulties, and good fortune and great"|FALSE
1|"energy are needed to hold them, and one of the greatest and most real"|FALSE
1|"helps would be that he who has acquired them should go and reside there."|FALSE
1|"This would make his position more secure and durable, as it has made"|FALSE
1|"that of the Turk in Greece, who, notwithstanding all the other measures"|FALSE
1|"taken by him for holding that state, if he had not settled there, would"|FALSE
1|"not have been able to keep it. Because, if one is on the spot, disorders"|FALSE
1|"are seen as they spring up, and one can quickly remedy them; but if one"|FALSE
1|"is not at hand, they are heard of only when they are great, and then one"|FALSE
1|"can no longer remedy them. Besides this, the country is not pillaged"|FALSE
1|"by your officials; the subjects are satisfied by prompt recourse to the"|FALSE
1|"prince; thus, wishing to be good, they have more cause to love him, and"|FALSE
1|"wishing to be otherwise, to fear him. He who would attack that state"|FALSE
1|"from the outside must have the utmost caution; as long as the prince"|FALSE
1|"resides there it can only be wrested from him with the greatest"|FALSE
1|"difficulty."|FALSE
1|"The other and better course is to send colonies to one or two places,"|FALSE
1|"which may be as keys to that state, for it is necessary either to do"|FALSE
1|"this or else to keep there a great number of cavalry and infantry. A"|FALSE
1|"prince does not spend much on colonies, for with little or no expense he"|FALSE
1|"can send them out and keep them there, and he offends a minority only of"|FALSE
1|"the citizens from whom he takes lands and houses to give them to the new"|FALSE
1|"inhabitants; and those whom he offends, remaining poor and scattered,"|FALSE
1|"are never able to injure him; whilst the rest being uninjured are easily"|FALSE
1|"kept quiet, and at the same time are anxious not to err for fear it"|FALSE
1|"should happen to them as it has to those who have been despoiled. In"|FALSE
1|"conclusion, I say that these colonies are not costly, they are more"|FALSE
1|"faithful, they injure less, and the injured, as has been said, being"|FALSE
1|"poor and scattered, cannot hurt. Upon this, one has to remark that men"|FALSE
1|"ought either to be well treated or crushed, because they can avenge"|FALSE
1|"themselves of lighter injuries, of more serious ones they cannot;"|FALSE
1|"therefore the injury that is to be done to a man ought to be of such a"|FALSE
1|"kind that one does not stand in fear of revenge."|FALSE
1|"But in maintaining armed men there in place of colonies one spends much"|FALSE
1|"more, having to consume on the garrison all the income from the"|FALSE
1|"state, so that the acquisition turns into a loss, and many more are"|FALSE
1|"exasperated, because the whole state is injured; through the shifting"|FALSE
1|"of the garrison up and down all become acquainted with hardship, and"|FALSE
1|"all become hostile, and they are enemies who, whilst beaten on their"|FALSE
1|"own ground, are yet able to do hurt. For every reason, therefore, such"|FALSE
1|"guards are as useless as a colony is useful."|FALSE
1|"Again, the prince who holds a country differing in the above respects"|FALSE
1|"ought to make himself the head and defender of his less powerful"|FALSE
1|"neighbours, and to weaken the more powerful amongst them, taking care"|FALSE
1|"that no foreigner as powerful as himself shall, by any accident, get"|FALSE
1|"a footing there; for it will always happen that such a one will be"|FALSE
1|"introduced by those who are discontented, either through excess of"|FALSE
1|"ambition or through fear, as one has seen already. The Romans were"|FALSE
1|"brought into Greece by the Aetolians; and in every other country where"|FALSE
1|"they obtained a footing they were brought in by the inhabitants. And the"|FALSE
1|"usual course of affairs is that, as soon as a powerful foreigner enters"|FALSE
1|"a country, all the subject states are drawn to him, moved by the hatred"|FALSE
1|"which they feel against the ruling power. So that in respect to those"|FALSE
1|"subject states he has not to take any trouble to gain them over to"|FALSE
1|"himself, for the whole of them quickly rally to the state which he has"|FALSE
1|"acquired there. He has only to take care that they do not get hold of"|FALSE
1|"too much power and too much authority, and then with his own forces, and"|FALSE
1|"with their goodwill, he can easily keep down the more powerful of them,"|FALSE
1|"so as to remain entirely master in the country. And he who does not"|FALSE
1|"properly manage this business will soon lose what he has acquired, and"|FALSE
1|"whilst he does hold it he will have endless difficulties and troubles."|FALSE
1|"The Romans, in the countries which they annexed, observed closely these"|FALSE
1|"measures; they sent colonies and maintained friendly relations with(*)"|FALSE
1|"the minor powers, without increasing their strength; they kept down the"|FALSE
1|"greater, and did not allow any strong foreign powers to gain authority."|FALSE
1|"Greece appears to me sufficient for an example. The Achaeans and"|FALSE
1|"Aetolians were kept friendly by them, the kingdom of Macedonia was"|FALSE
1|"humbled, Antiochus was driven out; yet the merits of the Achaeans and"|FALSE
1|"Aetolians never secured for them permission to increase their power, nor"|FALSE
1|"did the persuasions of Philip ever induce the Romans to be his friends"|FALSE
1|"without first humbling him, nor did the influence of Antiochus make them"|FALSE
1|"agree that he should retain any lordship over the country. Because the"|FALSE
1|"Romans did in these instances what all prudent princes ought to do,"|FALSE
1|"who have to regard not only present troubles, but also future ones, for"|FALSE
1|"which they must prepare with every energy, because, when foreseen, it is"|FALSE
1|"easy to remedy them; but if you wait until they approach, the medicine"|FALSE
1|"is no longer in time because the malady has become incurable; for it"|FALSE
1|"happens in this, as the physicians say it happens in hectic fever,"|FALSE
1|"that in the beginning of the malady it is easy to cure but difficult to"|FALSE
1|"detect, but in the course of time, not having been either detected or"|FALSE
1|"treated in the beginning, it becomes easy to detect but difficult to"|FALSE
1|"cure. This it happens in affairs of state, for when the evils that arise"|FALSE
1|"have been foreseen (which it is only given to a wise man to see), they"|FALSE
1|"can be quickly redressed, but when, through not having been foreseen,"|FALSE
1|"they have been permitted to grow in a way that every one can see them,"|FALSE
1|"there is no longer a remedy. Therefore, the Romans, foreseeing troubles,"|FALSE
1|"dealt with them at once, and, even to avoid a war, would not let them"|FALSE
1|"come to a head, for they knew that war is not to be avoided, but is only"|FALSE
1|"to be put off to the advantage of others; moreover they wished to fight"|FALSE
1|"with Philip and Antiochus in Greece so as not to have to do it in Italy;"|FALSE
1|"they could have avoided both, but this they did not wish; nor did that"|FALSE
1|"ever please them which is for ever in the mouths of the wise ones of our"|FALSE
1|"time:--Let us enjoy the benefits of the time--but rather the benefits of"|FALSE
1|"their own valour and prudence, for time drives everything before it, and"|FALSE
1|"is able to bring with it good as well as evil, and evil as well as good."|FALSE
1|"     (*) See remark in the introduction on the word"|FALSE
1|"     \"intrattenere.\""|FALSE
1|"But let us turn to France and inquire whether she has done any of the"|FALSE
1|"things mentioned. I will speak of Louis(*) (and not of Charles)(+) as"|FALSE
1|"the one whose conduct is the better to be observed, he having held"|FALSE
1|"possession of Italy for the longest period; and you will see that he"|FALSE
1|"has done the opposite to those things which ought to be done to retain a"|FALSE
1|"state composed of divers elements."|FALSE
1|"     (*) Louis XII, King of France, \"The Father of the People,\""|FALSE
1|"     born 1462, died 1515."|FALSE
1|"     (+) Charles VIII, King of France, born 1470, died 1498."|FALSE
1|"King Louis was brought into Italy by the ambition of the Venetians, who"|FALSE
1|"desired to obtain half the state of Lombardy by his intervention. I"|FALSE
1|"will not blame the course taken by the king, because, wishing to get a"|FALSE
1|"foothold in Italy, and having no friends there--seeing rather that every"|FALSE
1|"door was shut to him owing to the conduct of Charles--he was forced to"|FALSE
1|"accept those friendships which he could get, and he would have succeeded"|FALSE
1|"very quickly in his design if in other matters he had not made some"|FALSE
1|"mistakes. The king, however, having acquired Lombardy, regained at once"|FALSE
1|"the authority which Charles had lost: Genoa yielded; the Florentines"|FALSE
1|"became his friends; the Marquess of Mantua, the Duke of Ferrara, the"|FALSE
1|"Bentivogli, my lady of Forli, the Lords of Faenza, of Pesaro, of"|FALSE
1|"Rimini, of Camerino, of Piombino, the Lucchese, the Pisans, the"|FALSE
1|"Sienese--everybody made advances to him to become his friend. Then could"|FALSE
1|"the Venetians realize the rashness of the course taken by them, which,"|FALSE
1|"in order that they might secure two towns in Lombardy, had made the king"|FALSE
1|"master of two-thirds of Italy."|FALSE
1|"Let any one now consider with what little difficulty the king could have"|FALSE
1|"maintained his position in Italy had he observed the rules above laid"|FALSE
1|"down, and kept all his friends secure and protected; for although they"|FALSE
1|"were numerous they were both weak and timid, some afraid of the Church,"|FALSE
1|"some of the Venetians, and thus they would always have been forced to"|FALSE
1|"stand in with him, and by their means he could easily have made himself"|FALSE
1|"secure against those who remained powerful. But he was no sooner in"|FALSE
1|"Milan than he did the contrary by assisting Pope Alexander to occupy the"|FALSE
1|"Romagna. It never occurred to him that by this action he was weakening"|FALSE
1|"himself, depriving himself of friends and of those who had thrown"|FALSE
1|"themselves into his lap, whilst he aggrandized the Church by adding much"|FALSE
1|"temporal power to the spiritual, thus giving it greater authority. And"|FALSE
1|"having committed this prime error, he was obliged to follow it up, so"|FALSE
1|"much so that, to put an end to the ambition of Alexander, and to prevent"|FALSE
1|"his becoming the master of Tuscany, he was himself forced to come into"|FALSE
1|"Italy."|FALSE
1|"And as if it were not enough to have aggrandized the Church, and"|FALSE
1|"deprived himself of friends, he, wishing to have the kingdom of Naples,"|FALSE
1|"divides it with the King of Spain, and where he was the prime arbiter in"|FALSE
1|"Italy he takes an associate, so that the ambitious of that country and"|FALSE
1|"the malcontents of his own should have somewhere to shelter; and whereas"|FALSE
1|"he could have left in the kingdom his own pensioner as king, he drove"|FALSE
1|"him out, to put one there who was able to drive him, Louis, out in turn."|FALSE
1|"The wish to acquire is in truth very natural and common, and men always"|FALSE
1|"do so when they can, and for this they will be praised not blamed; but"|FALSE
1|"when they cannot do so, yet wish to do so by any means, then there is"|FALSE
1|"folly and blame. Therefore, if France could have attacked Naples with"|FALSE
1|"her own forces she ought to have done so; if she could not, then she"|FALSE
1|"ought not to have divided it. And if the partition which she made with"|FALSE
1|"the Venetians in Lombardy was justified by the excuse that by it she got"|FALSE
1|"a foothold in Italy, this other partition merited blame, for it had not"|FALSE
1|"the excuse of that necessity."|FALSE
1|"Therefore Louis made these five errors: he destroyed the minor powers,"|FALSE
1|"he increased the strength of one of the greater powers in Italy, he"|FALSE
1|"brought in a foreign power, he did not settle in the country, he did not"|FALSE
1|"send colonies. Which errors, had he lived, were not enough to injure"|FALSE
1|"him had he not made a sixth by taking away their dominions from the"|FALSE
1|"Venetians; because, had he not aggrandized the Church, nor brought Spain"|FALSE
1|"into Italy, it would have been very reasonable and necessary to humble"|FALSE
1|"them; but having first taken these steps, he ought never to have"|FALSE
1|"consented to their ruin, for they, being powerful, would always have"|FALSE
1|"kept off others from designs on Lombardy, to which the Venetians would"|FALSE
1|"never have consented except to become masters themselves there; also"|FALSE
1|"because the others would not wish to take Lombardy from France in order"|FALSE
1|"to give it to the Venetians, and to run counter to both they would not"|FALSE
1|"have had the courage."|FALSE
1|"And if any one should say: \"King Louis yielded the Romagna to Alexander"|FALSE
1|"and the kingdom to Spain to avoid war,\" I answer for the reasons given"|FALSE
1|"above that a blunder ought never to be perpetrated to avoid war, because"|FALSE
1|"it is not to be avoided, but is only deferred to your disadvantage. And"|FALSE
1|"if another should allege the pledge which the king had given to the"|FALSE
1|"Pope that he would assist him in the enterprise, in exchange for the"|FALSE
1|"dissolution of his marriage(*) and for the cap to Rouen,(+) to that I"|FALSE
1|"reply what I shall write later on concerning the faith of princes, and"|FALSE
1|"how it ought to be kept."|FALSE
1|"     (*) Louis XII divorced his wife, Jeanne, daughter of Louis"|FALSE
1|"     XI, and married in 1499 Anne of Brittany, widow of Charles"|FALSE
1|"     VIII, in order to retain the Duchy of Brittany for the"|FALSE
1|"     crown."|FALSE
1|"     (+) The Archbishop of Rouen. He was Georges d'Amboise,"|FALSE
1|"     created a cardinal by Alexander VI. Born 1460, died 1510."|FALSE
1|"Thus King Louis lost Lombardy by not having followed any of the"|FALSE
1|"conditions observed by those who have taken possession of countries and"|FALSE
1|"wished to retain them. Nor is there any miracle in this, but much that"|FALSE
1|"is reasonable and quite natural. And on these matters I spoke at Nantes"|FALSE
1|"with Rouen, when Valentino, as Cesare Borgia, the son of Pope Alexander,"|FALSE
1|"was usually called, occupied the Romagna, and on Cardinal Rouen"|FALSE
1|"observing to me that the Italians did not understand war, I replied"|FALSE
1|"to him that the French did not understand statecraft, meaning that"|FALSE
1|"otherwise they would not have allowed the Church to reach such"|FALSE
1|"greatness. And in fact it has been seen that the greatness of the Church"|FALSE
1|"and of Spain in Italy has been caused by France, and her ruin may be"|FALSE
1|"attributed to them. From this a general rule is drawn which never or"|FALSE
1|"rarely fails: that he who is the cause of another becoming powerful"|FALSE
1|"is ruined; because that predominancy has been brought about either by"|FALSE
1|"astuteness or else by force, and both are distrusted by him who has been"|FALSE
1|"raised to power."|FALSE
1|"CHAPTER IV -- WHY THE KINGDOM OF DARIUS, CONQUERED BY ALEXANDER, DID NOT"|FALSE
1|"REBEL AGAINST THE SUCCESSORS OF ALEXANDER AT HIS DEATH"|FALSE
1|"Considering the difficulties which men have had to hold to a newly"|FALSE
1|"acquired state, some might wonder how, seeing that Alexander the"|FALSE
1|"Great became the master of Asia in a few years, and died whilst it"|FALSE
1|"was scarcely settled (whence it might appear reasonable that the whole"|FALSE
1|"empire would have rebelled), nevertheless his successors maintained"|FALSE
1|"themselves, and had to meet no other difficulty than that which arose"|FALSE
1|"among themselves from their own ambitions."|FALSE
1|"I answer that the principalities of which one has record are found to"|FALSE
1|"be governed in two different ways; either by a prince, with a body"|FALSE
1|"of servants, who assist him to govern the kingdom as ministers by his"|FALSE
1|"favour and permission; or by a prince and barons, who hold that dignity"|FALSE
1|"by antiquity of blood and not by the grace of the prince. Such barons"|FALSE
1|"have states and their own subjects, who recognize them as lords and hold"|FALSE
1|"them in natural affection. Those states that are governed by a prince"|FALSE
1|"and his servants hold their prince in more consideration, because in all"|FALSE
1|"the country there is no one who is recognized as superior to him, and"|FALSE
1|"if they yield obedience to another they do it as to a minister and"|FALSE
1|"official, and they do not bear him any particular affection."|FALSE
1|"The examples of these two governments in our time are the Turk and the"|FALSE
1|"King of France. The entire monarchy of the Turk is governed by one lord,"|FALSE
1|"the others are his servants; and, dividing his kingdom into sanjaks, he"|FALSE
1|"sends there different administrators, and shifts and changes them as"|FALSE
1|"he chooses. But the King of France is placed in the midst of an ancient"|FALSE
1|"body of lords, acknowledged by their own subjects, and beloved by them;"|FALSE
1|"they have their own prerogatives, nor can the king take these away"|FALSE
1|"except at his peril. Therefore, he who considers both of these states"|FALSE
1|"will recognize great difficulties in seizing the state of the Turk,"|FALSE
1|"but, once it is conquered, great ease in holding it. The causes of the"|FALSE
1|"difficulties in seizing the kingdom of the Turk are that the usurper"|FALSE
1|"cannot be called in by the princes of the kingdom, nor can he hope to be"|FALSE
1|"assisted in his designs by the revolt of those whom the lord has around"|FALSE
1|"him. This arises from the reasons given above; for his ministers, being"|FALSE
1|"all slaves and bondmen, can only be corrupted with great difficulty, and"|FALSE
1|"one can expect little advantage from them when they have been corrupted,"|FALSE
1|"as they cannot carry the people with them, for the reasons assigned."|FALSE
1|"Hence, he who attacks the Turk must bear in mind that he will find him"|FALSE
1|"united, and he will have to rely more on his own strength than on the"|FALSE
1|"revolt of others; but, if once the Turk has been conquered, and routed"|FALSE
1|"in the field in such a way that he cannot replace his armies, there"|FALSE
1|"is nothing to fear but the family of this prince, and, this being"|FALSE
1|"exterminated, there remains no one to fear, the others having no credit"|FALSE
