1|"CHAPTER V -- CONCERNING THE WAY TO GOVERN CITIES OR PRINCIPALITIES WHICH"|FALSE
1|"LIVED UNDER THEIR OWN LAWS BEFORE THEY WERE ANNEXED"|FALSE
1|"Whenever those states which have been acquired as stated have been"|FALSE
1|"accustomed to live under their own laws and in freedom, there are three"|FALSE
1|"courses for those who wish to hold them: the first is to ruin them, the"|FALSE
1|"next is to reside there in person, the third is to permit them to live"|FALSE
1|"under their own laws, drawing a tribute, and establishing within it an"|FALSE
1|"oligarchy which will keep it friendly to you. Because such a government,"|FALSE
1|"being created by the prince, knows that it cannot stand without"|FALSE
1|"his friendship and interest, and does it utmost to support him; and"|FALSE
1|"therefore he who would keep a city accustomed to freedom will hold it"|FALSE
1|"more easily by the means of its own citizens than in any other way."|FALSE
1|"There are, for example, the Spartans and the Romans. The Spartans held"|FALSE
1|"Athens and Thebes, establishing there an oligarchy, nevertheless they"|FALSE
1|"lost them. The Romans, in order to hold Capua, Carthage, and Numantia,"|FALSE
1|"dismantled them, and did not lose them. They wished to hold Greece as"|FALSE
1|"the Spartans held it, making it free and permitting its laws, and did"|FALSE
1|"not succeed. So to hold it they were compelled to dismantle many"|FALSE
1|"cities in the country, for in truth there is no safe way to retain them"|FALSE
1|"otherwise than by ruining them. And he who becomes master of a city"|FALSE
1|"accustomed to freedom and does not destroy it, may expect to be"|FALSE
1|"destroyed by it, for in rebellion it has always the watchword of liberty"|FALSE
1|"and its ancient privileges as a rallying point, which neither time"|FALSE
1|"nor benefits will ever cause it to forget. And whatever you may do or"|FALSE
1|"provide against, they never forget that name or their privileges unless"|FALSE
1|"they are disunited or dispersed, but at every chance they immediately"|FALSE
1|"rally to them, as Pisa after the hundred years she had been held in"|FALSE
1|"bondage by the Florentines."|FALSE
1|"But when cities or countries are accustomed to live under a prince, and"|FALSE
1|"his family is exterminated, they, being on the one hand accustomed to"|FALSE
1|"obey and on the other hand not having the old prince, cannot agree in"|FALSE
1|"making one from amongst themselves, and they do not know how to govern"|FALSE
1|"themselves. For this reason they are very slow to take up arms, and a"|FALSE
1|"prince can gain them to himself and secure them much more easily. But"|FALSE
1|"in republics there is more vitality, greater hatred, and more desire"|FALSE
1|"for vengeance, which will never permit them to allow the memory of their"|FALSE
1|"former liberty to rest; so that the safest way is to destroy them or to"|FALSE
1|"reside there."|FALSE
1|"CHAPTER VI -- CONCERNING NEW PRINCIPALITIES WHICH ARE ACQUIRED BY ONE'S"|FALSE
1|"OWN ARMS AND ABILITY"|FALSE
1|"Let no one be surprised if, in speaking of entirely new principalities"|FALSE
1|"as I shall do, I adduce the highest examples both of prince and of"|FALSE
1|"state; because men, walking almost always in paths beaten by others, and"|FALSE
1|"following by imitation their deeds, are yet unable to keep entirely to"|FALSE
1|"the ways of others or attain to the power of those they imitate. A wise"|FALSE
1|"man ought always to follow the paths beaten by great men, and to imitate"|FALSE
1|"those who have been supreme, so that if his ability does not equal"|FALSE
1|"theirs, at least it will savour of it. Let him act like the clever"|FALSE
1|"archers who, designing to hit the mark which yet appears too far"|FALSE
1|"distant, and knowing the limits to which the strength of their bow"|FALSE
1|"attains, take aim much higher than the mark, not to reach by their"|FALSE
1|"strength or arrow to so great a height, but to be able with the aid of"|FALSE
1|"so high an aim to hit the mark they wish to reach."|FALSE
1|"I say, therefore, that in entirely new principalities, where there is"|FALSE
1|"a new prince, more or less difficulty is found in keeping them,"|FALSE
1|"accordingly as there is more or less ability in him who has acquired"|FALSE
1|"the state. Now, as the fact of becoming a prince from a private station"|FALSE
1|"presupposes either ability or fortune, it is clear that one or other"|FALSE
1|"of these things will mitigate in some degree many difficulties."|FALSE
1|"Nevertheless, he who has relied least on fortune is established the"|FALSE
1|"strongest. Further, it facilitates matters when the prince, having no"|FALSE
1|"other state, is compelled to reside there in person."|FALSE
1|"But to come to those who, by their own ability and not through fortune,"|FALSE
1|"have risen to be princes, I say that Moses, Cyrus, Romulus, Theseus,"|FALSE
1|"and such like are the most excellent examples. And although one may not"|FALSE
1|"discuss Moses, he having been a mere executor of the will of God, yet"|FALSE
1|"he ought to be admired, if only for that favour which made him worthy to"|FALSE
1|"speak with God. But in considering Cyrus and others who have acquired or"|FALSE
1|"founded kingdoms, all will be found admirable; and if their particular"|FALSE
1|"deeds and conduct shall be considered, they will not be found inferior"|FALSE
1|"to those of Moses, although he had so great a preceptor. And in"|FALSE
1|"examining their actions and lives one cannot see that they owed anything"|FALSE
1|"to fortune beyond opportunity, which brought them the material to mould"|FALSE
1|"into the form which seemed best to them. Without that opportunity their"|FALSE
1|"powers of mind would have been extinguished, and without those powers"|FALSE
1|"the opportunity would have come in vain."|FALSE
1|"It was necessary, therefore, to Moses that he should find the people of"|FALSE
1|"Israel in Egypt enslaved and oppressed by the Egyptians, in order that"|FALSE
1|"they should be disposed to follow him so as to be delivered out of"|FALSE
1|"bondage. It was necessary that Romulus should not remain in Alba, and"|FALSE
1|"that he should be abandoned at his birth, in order that he should become"|FALSE
1|"King of Rome and founder of the fatherland. It was necessary that Cyrus"|FALSE
1|"should find the Persians discontented with the government of the Medes,"|FALSE
1|"and the Medes soft and effeminate through their long peace. Theseus"|FALSE
1|"could not have shown his ability had he not found the Athenians"|FALSE
1|"dispersed. These opportunities, therefore, made those men fortunate,"|FALSE
1|"and their high ability enabled them to recognize the opportunity whereby"|FALSE
1|"their country was ennobled and made famous."|FALSE
1|"Those who by valorous ways become princes, like these men, acquire"|FALSE
1|"a principality with difficulty, but they keep it with ease. The"|FALSE
1|"difficulties they have in acquiring it rise in part from the new rules"|FALSE
1|"and methods which they are forced to introduce to establish their"|FALSE
1|"government and its security. And it ought to be remembered that there"|FALSE
1|"is nothing more difficult to take in hand, more perilous to conduct, or"|FALSE
1|"more uncertain in its success, than to take the lead in the introduction"|FALSE
1|"of a new order of things, because the innovator has for enemies"|FALSE
1|"all those who have done well under the old conditions, and lukewarm"|FALSE
1|"defenders in those who may do well under the new. This coolness arises"|FALSE
1|"partly from fear of the opponents, who have the laws on their side, and"|FALSE
1|"partly from the incredulity of men, who do not readily believe in new"|FALSE
1|"things until they have had a long experience of them. Thus it happens"|FALSE
1|"that whenever those who are hostile have the opportunity to attack they"|FALSE
1|"do it like partisans, whilst the others defend lukewarmly, in such wise"|FALSE
1|"that the prince is endangered along with them."|FALSE
1|"It is necessary, therefore, if we desire to discuss this matter"|FALSE
1|"thoroughly, to inquire whether these innovators can rely on themselves"|FALSE
1|"or have to depend on others: that is to say, whether, to consummate"|FALSE
1|"their enterprise, have they to use prayers or can they use force? In the"|FALSE
1|"first instance they always succeed badly, and never compass anything;"|FALSE
1|"but when they can rely on themselves and use force, then they are rarely"|FALSE
1|"endangered. Hence it is that all armed prophets have conquered, and the"|FALSE
1|"unarmed ones have been destroyed. Besides the reasons mentioned, the"|FALSE
1|"nature of the people is variable, and whilst it is easy to persuade"|FALSE
1|"them, it is difficult to fix them in that persuasion. And thus it is"|FALSE
1|"necessary to take such measures that, when they believe no longer, it"|FALSE
1|"may be possible to make them believe by force."|FALSE
1|"If Moses, Cyrus, Theseus, and Romulus had been unarmed they could not"|FALSE
1|"have enforced their constitutions for long--as happened in our time to"|FALSE
1|"Fra Girolamo Savonarola, who was ruined with his new order of things"|FALSE
1|"immediately the multitude believed in him no longer, and he had no means"|FALSE
1|"of keeping steadfast those who believed or of making the unbelievers to"|FALSE
1|"believe. Therefore such as these have great difficulties in consummating"|FALSE
1|"their enterprise, for all their dangers are in the ascent, yet with"|FALSE
1|"ability they will overcome them; but when these are overcome, and those"|FALSE
1|"who envied them their success are exterminated, they will begin to be"|FALSE
1|"respected, and they will continue afterwards powerful, secure, honoured,"|FALSE
1|"and happy."|FALSE
1|"To these great examples I wish to add a lesser one; still it bears some"|FALSE
1|"resemblance to them, and I wish it to suffice me for all of a like kind:"|FALSE
1|"it is Hiero the Syracusan.(*) This man rose from a private station to"|FALSE
1|"be Prince of Syracuse, nor did he, either, owe anything to fortune but"|FALSE
1|"opportunity; for the Syracusans, being oppressed, chose him for their"|FALSE
1|"captain, afterwards he was rewarded by being made their prince. He was"|FALSE
1|"of so great ability, even as a private citizen, that one who writes"|FALSE
1|"of him says he wanted nothing but a kingdom to be a king. This man"|FALSE
1|"abolished the old soldiery, organized the new, gave up old alliances,"|FALSE
1|"made new ones; and as he had his own soldiers and allies, on such"|FALSE
1|"foundations he was able to build any edifice: thus, whilst he had"|FALSE
1|"endured much trouble in acquiring, he had but little in keeping."|FALSE
1|"     (*) Hiero II, born about 307 B.C., died 216 B.C."|FALSE
1|"CHAPTER VII -- CONCERNING NEW PRINCIPALITIES WHICH ARE ACQUIRED EITHER"|FALSE
1|"BY THE ARMS OF OTHERS OR BY GOOD FORTUNE"|FALSE
1|"Those who solely by good fortune become princes from being private"|FALSE
1|"citizens have little trouble in rising, but much in keeping atop; they"|FALSE
1|"have not any difficulties on the way up, because they fly, but they have"|FALSE
1|"many when they reach the summit. Such are those to whom some state"|FALSE
1|"is given either for money or by the favour of him who bestows it;"|FALSE
1|"as happened to many in Greece, in the cities of Ionia and of the"|FALSE
1|"Hellespont, where princes were made by Darius, in order that they might"|FALSE
1|"hold the cities both for his security and his glory; as also were those"|FALSE
1|"emperors who, by the corruption of the soldiers, from being citizens"|FALSE
1|"came to empire. Such stand simply elevated upon the goodwill and the"|FALSE
1|"fortune of him who has elevated them--two most inconstant and unstable"|FALSE
1|"things. Neither have they the knowledge requisite for the position;"|FALSE
1|"because, unless they are men of great worth and ability, it is not"|FALSE
1|"reasonable to expect that they should know how to command, having always"|FALSE
1|"lived in a private condition; besides, they cannot hold it because they"|FALSE
1|"have not forces which they can keep friendly and faithful."|FALSE
1|"States that rise unexpectedly, then, like all other things in nature"|FALSE
1|"which are born and grow rapidly, cannot leave their foundations and"|FALSE
1|"correspondencies(*) fixed in such a way that the first storm will"|FALSE
1|"not overthrow them; unless, as is said, those who unexpectedly become"|FALSE
1|"princes are men of so much ability that they know they have to be"|FALSE
1|"prepared at once to hold that which fortune has thrown into their laps,"|FALSE
1|"and that those foundations, which others have laid BEFORE they became"|FALSE
1|"princes, they must lay AFTERWARDS."|FALSE
1|"     (*) \"Le radici e corrispondenze,\" their roots (i.e."|FALSE
1|"     foundations) and correspondencies or relations with other"|FALSE
1|"     states--a common meaning of \"correspondence\" and"|FALSE
1|"     \"correspondency\" in the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries."|FALSE
1|"Concerning these two methods of rising to be a prince by ability or"|FALSE
1|"fortune, I wish to adduce two examples within our own recollection, and"|FALSE
1|"these are Francesco Sforza(*) and Cesare Borgia. Francesco, by proper"|FALSE
1|"means and with great ability, from being a private person rose to be"|FALSE
1|"Duke of Milan, and that which he had acquired with a thousand anxieties"|FALSE
1|"he kept with little trouble. On the other hand, Cesare Borgia, called by"|FALSE
1|"the people Duke Valentino, acquired his state during the ascendancy of"|FALSE
1|"his father, and on its decline he lost it, notwithstanding that he had"|FALSE
1|"taken every measure and done all that ought to be done by a wise and"|FALSE
1|"able man to fix firmly his roots in the states which the arms and"|FALSE
1|"fortunes of others had bestowed on him."|FALSE
1|"     (*) Francesco Sforza, born 1401, died 1466. He married"|FALSE
1|"     Bianca Maria Visconti, a natural daughter of Filippo"|FALSE
1|"     Visconti, the Duke of Milan, on whose death he procured his"|FALSE
1|"     own elevation to the duchy. Machiavelli was the accredited"|FALSE
1|"     agent of the Florentine Republic to Cesare Borgia (1478-"|FALSE
1|"     1507) during the transactions which led up to the"|FALSE
1|"     assassinations of the Orsini and Vitelli at Sinigalia, and"|FALSE
1|"     along with his letters to his chiefs in Florence he has left"|FALSE
1|"     an account, written ten years before \"The Prince,\" of the"|FALSE
1|"     proceedings of the duke in his \"Descritione del modo tenuto"|FALSE
1|"     dal duca Valentino nello ammazzare Vitellozzo Vitelli,\""|FALSE
1|"     etc., a translation of which is appended to the present"|FALSE
1|"     work."|FALSE
1|"Because, as is stated above, he who has not first laid his foundations"|FALSE
1|"may be able with great ability to lay them afterwards, but they will"|FALSE
1|"be laid with trouble to the architect and danger to the building. If,"|FALSE
1|"therefore, all the steps taken by the duke be considered, it will be"|FALSE
1|"seen that he laid solid foundations for his future power, and I do not"|FALSE
1|"consider it superfluous to discuss them, because I do not know what"|FALSE
1|"better precepts to give a new prince than the example of his actions;"|FALSE
1|"and if his dispositions were of no avail, that was not his fault, but"|FALSE
1|"the extraordinary and extreme malignity of fortune."|FALSE
1|"Alexander the Sixth, in wishing to aggrandize the duke, his son, had"|FALSE
1|"many immediate and prospective difficulties. Firstly, he did not see his"|FALSE
1|"way to make him master of any state that was not a state of the Church;"|FALSE
1|"and if he was willing to rob the Church he knew that the Duke of Milan"|FALSE
1|"and the Venetians would not consent, because Faenza and Rimini were"|FALSE
1|"already under the protection of the Venetians. Besides this, he saw the"|FALSE
1|"arms of Italy, especially those by which he might have been assisted, in"|FALSE
1|"hands that would fear the aggrandizement of the Pope, namely, the Orsini"|FALSE
1|"and the Colonnesi and their following. It behoved him, therefore,"|FALSE
1|"to upset this state of affairs and embroil the powers, so as to make"|FALSE
1|"himself securely master of part of their states. This was easy for him"|FALSE
1|"to do, because he found the Venetians, moved by other reasons, inclined"|FALSE
1|"to bring back the French into Italy; he would not only not oppose this,"|FALSE
1|"but he would render it more easy by dissolving the former marriage of"|FALSE
1|"King Louis. Therefore the king came into Italy with the assistance of"|FALSE
1|"the Venetians and the consent of Alexander. He was no sooner in Milan"|FALSE
1|"than the Pope had soldiers from him for the attempt on the Romagna,"|FALSE
1|"which yielded to him on the reputation of the king. The duke, therefore,"|FALSE
1|"having acquired the Romagna and beaten the Colonnesi, while wishing to"|FALSE
1|"hold that and to advance further, was hindered by two things: the one,"|FALSE
1|"his forces did not appear loyal to him, the other, the goodwill of"|FALSE
1|"France: that is to say, he feared that the forces of the Orsini, which"|FALSE
1|"he was using, would not stand to him, that not only might they hinder"|FALSE
1|"him from winning more, but might themselves seize what he had won, and"|FALSE
1|"that the king might also do the same. Of the Orsini he had a warning"|FALSE
1|"when, after taking Faenza and attacking Bologna, he saw them go very"|FALSE
1|"unwillingly to that attack. And as to the king, he learned his mind when"|FALSE
1|"he himself, after taking the Duchy of Urbino, attacked Tuscany, and the"|FALSE
1|"king made him desist from that undertaking; hence the duke decided to"|FALSE
1|"depend no more upon the arms and the luck of others."|FALSE
1|"For the first thing he weakened the Orsini and Colonnesi parties in"|FALSE
1|"Rome, by gaining to himself all their adherents who were gentlemen,"|FALSE
1|"making them his gentlemen, giving them good pay, and, according to their"|FALSE
1|"rank, honouring them with office and command in such a way that in a few"|FALSE
1|"months all attachment to the factions was destroyed and turned entirely"|FALSE
1|"to the duke. After this he awaited an opportunity to crush the Orsini,"|FALSE
1|"having scattered the adherents of the Colonna house. This came to him"|FALSE
1|"soon and he used it well; for the Orsini, perceiving at length that the"|FALSE
1|"aggrandizement of the duke and the Church was ruin to them, called a"|FALSE
1|"meeting of the Magione in Perugia. From this sprung the rebellion at"|FALSE
1|"Urbino and the tumults in the Romagna, with endless dangers to the duke,"|FALSE
1|"all of which he overcame with the help of the French. Having restored"|FALSE
1|"his authority, not to leave it at risk by trusting either to the French"|FALSE
1|"or other outside forces, he had recourse to his wiles, and he knew"|FALSE
1|"so well how to conceal his mind that, by the mediation of Signor"|FALSE
1|"Pagolo--whom the duke did not fail to secure with all kinds of"|FALSE
1|"attention, giving him money, apparel, and horses--the Orsini were"|FALSE
1|"reconciled, so that their simplicity brought them into his power"|FALSE
1|"at Sinigalia.(*) Having exterminated the leaders, and turned their"|FALSE
1|"partisans into his friends, the duke laid sufficiently good foundations"|FALSE
1|"to his power, having all the Romagna and the Duchy of Urbino; and the"|FALSE
1|"people now beginning to appreciate their prosperity, he gained them"|FALSE
1|"all over to himself. And as this point is worthy of notice, and to be"|FALSE
1|"imitated by others, I am not willing to leave it out."|FALSE
1|"     (*) Sinigalia, 31st December 1502."|FALSE
1|"When the duke occupied the Romagna he found it under the rule of weak"|FALSE
1|"masters, who rather plundered their subjects than ruled them, and gave"|FALSE
1|"them more cause for disunion than for union, so that the country was"|FALSE
1|"full of robbery, quarrels, and every kind of violence; and so, wishing"|FALSE
1|"to bring back peace and obedience to authority, he considered it"|FALSE
1|"necessary to give it a good governor. Thereupon he promoted Messer"|FALSE
1|"Ramiro d'Orco,(*) a swift and cruel man, to whom he gave the fullest"|FALSE
1|"power. This man in a short time restored peace and unity with the"|FALSE
1|"greatest success. Afterwards the duke considered that it was not"|FALSE
1|"advisable to confer such excessive authority, for he had no doubt but"|FALSE
1|"that he would become odious, so he set up a court of judgment in the"|FALSE
1|"country, under a most excellent president, wherein all cities had their"|FALSE
1|"advocates. And because he knew that the past severity had caused some"|FALSE
1|"hatred against himself, so, to clear himself in the minds of the people,"|FALSE
1|"and gain them entirely to himself, he desired to show that, if any"|FALSE
1|"cruelty had been practised, it had not originated with him, but in the"|FALSE
1|"natural sternness of the minister. Under this pretence he took Ramiro,"|FALSE
1|"and one morning caused him to be executed and left on the piazza at"|FALSE
1|"Cesena with the block and a bloody knife at his side. The barbarity of"|FALSE
1|"this spectacle caused the people to be at once satisfied and dismayed."|FALSE
1|"     (*) Ramiro d'Orco. Ramiro de Lorqua."|FALSE
1|"But let us return whence we started. I say that the duke, finding"|FALSE
1|"himself now sufficiently powerful and partly secured from immediate"|FALSE
1|"dangers by having armed himself in his own way, and having in a great"|FALSE
1|"measure crushed those forces in his vicinity that could injure him if he"|FALSE
1|"wished to proceed with his conquest, had next to consider France, for"|FALSE
1|"he knew that the king, who too late was aware of his mistake, would not"|FALSE
1|"support him. And from this time he began to seek new alliances and to"|FALSE
1|"temporize with France in the expedition which she was making towards the"|FALSE
1|"kingdom of Naples against the Spaniards who were besieging Gaeta. It"|FALSE
1|"was his intention to secure himself against them, and this he would have"|FALSE
1|"quickly accomplished had Alexander lived."|FALSE
1|"Such was his line of action as to present affairs. But as to the future"|FALSE
1|"he had to fear, in the first place, that a new successor to the Church"|FALSE
1|"might not be friendly to him and might seek to take from him that which"|FALSE
1|"Alexander had given him, so he decided to act in four ways. Firstly, by"|FALSE
1|"exterminating the families of those lords whom he had despoiled, so as"|FALSE
1|"to take away that pretext from the Pope. Secondly, by winning to himself"|FALSE
1|"all the gentlemen of Rome, so as to be able to curb the Pope with their"|FALSE
1|"aid, as has been observed. Thirdly, by converting the college more to"|FALSE
1|"himself. Fourthly, by acquiring so much power before the Pope should die"|FALSE
1|"that he could by his own measures resist the first shock. Of these four"|FALSE
1|"things, at the death of Alexander, he had accomplished three. For he had"|FALSE
1|"killed as many of the dispossessed lords as he could lay hands on, and"|FALSE
1|"few had escaped; he had won over the Roman gentlemen, and he had the"|FALSE
1|"most numerous party in the college. And as to any fresh acquisition, he"|FALSE
1|"intended to become master of Tuscany, for he already possessed Perugia"|FALSE
1|"and Piombino, and Pisa was under his protection. And as he had no longer"|FALSE
1|"to study France (for the French were already driven out of the kingdom"|FALSE
1|"of Naples by the Spaniards, and in this way both were compelled to buy"|FALSE
1|"his goodwill), he pounced down upon Pisa. After this, Lucca and Siena"|FALSE
1|"yielded at once, partly through hatred and partly through fear of"|FALSE
1|"the Florentines; and the Florentines would have had no remedy had he"|FALSE
1|"continued to prosper, as he was prospering the year that Alexander died,"|FALSE
1|"for he had acquired so much power and reputation that he would have"|FALSE
1|"stood by himself, and no longer have depended on the luck and the forces"|FALSE
1|"of others, but solely on his own power and ability."|FALSE
1|"But Alexander died five years after he had first drawn the sword. He"|FALSE
1|"left the duke with the state of Romagna alone consolidated, with the"|FALSE
1|"rest in the air, between two most powerful hostile armies, and sick unto"|FALSE
1|"death. Yet there were in the duke such boldness and ability, and he knew"|FALSE
1|"so well how men are to be won or lost, and so firm were the foundations"|FALSE
1|"which in so short a time he had laid, that if he had not had those"|FALSE
1|"armies on his back, or if he had been in good health, he would have"|FALSE
1|"overcome all difficulties. And it is seen that his foundations were"|FALSE
1|"good, for the Romagna awaited him for more than a month. In Rome,"|FALSE
1|"although but half alive, he remained secure; and whilst the Baglioni,"|FALSE
1|"the Vitelli, and the Orsini might come to Rome, they could not effect"|FALSE
1|"anything against him. If he could not have made Pope him whom he wished,"|FALSE
1|"at least the one whom he did not wish would not have been elected. But"|FALSE
1|"if he had been in sound health at the death of Alexander,(*) everything"|FALSE
1|"would have been different to him. On the day that Julius the Second(+)"|FALSE
1|"was elected, he told me that he had thought of everything that might"|FALSE
1|"occur at the death of his father, and had provided a remedy for all,"|FALSE
