1|"CHAPTER VIII -- CONCERNING THOSE WHO HAVE OBTAINED A PRINCIPALITY BY"|FALSE
1|"WICKEDNESS"|FALSE
1|"Although a prince may rise from a private station in two ways, neither"|FALSE
1|"of which can be entirely attributed to fortune or genius, yet it is"|FALSE
1|"manifest to me that I must not be silent on them, although one could be"|FALSE
1|"more copiously treated when I discuss republics. These methods are"|FALSE
1|"when, either by some wicked or nefarious ways, one ascends to the"|FALSE
1|"principality, or when by the favour of his fellow-citizens a private"|FALSE
1|"person becomes the prince of his country. And speaking of the first"|FALSE
1|"method, it will be illustrated by two examples--one ancient, the other"|FALSE
1|"modern--and without entering further into the subject, I consider these"|FALSE
1|"two examples will suffice those who may be compelled to follow them."|FALSE
1|"Agathocles, the Sicilian,(*) became King of Syracuse not only from"|FALSE
1|"a private but from a low and abject position. This man, the son of a"|FALSE
1|"potter, through all the changes in his fortunes always led an infamous"|FALSE
1|"life. Nevertheless, he accompanied his infamies with so much ability of"|FALSE
1|"mind and body that, having devoted himself to the military profession,"|FALSE
1|"he rose through its ranks to be Praetor of Syracuse. Being established"|FALSE
1|"in that position, and having deliberately resolved to make himself"|FALSE
1|"prince and to seize by violence, without obligation to others, that"|FALSE
1|"which had been conceded to him by assent, he came to an understanding"|FALSE
1|"for this purpose with Amilcar, the Carthaginian, who, with his army, was"|FALSE
1|"fighting in Sicily. One morning he assembled the people and the senate"|FALSE
1|"of Syracuse, as if he had to discuss with them things relating to the"|FALSE
1|"Republic, and at a given signal the soldiers killed all the senators and"|FALSE
1|"the richest of the people; these dead, he seized and held the princedom"|FALSE
1|"of that city without any civil commotion. And although he was twice"|FALSE
1|"routed by the Carthaginians, and ultimately besieged, yet not only was"|FALSE
1|"he able to defend his city, but leaving part of his men for its defence,"|FALSE
1|"with the others he attacked Africa, and in a short time raised the"|FALSE
1|"siege of Syracuse. The Carthaginians, reduced to extreme necessity, were"|FALSE
1|"compelled to come to terms with Agathocles, and, leaving Sicily to him,"|FALSE
1|"had to be content with the possession of Africa."|FALSE
1|"     (*) Agathocles the Sicilian, born 361 B.C., died 289 B.C."|FALSE
1|"Therefore, he who considers the actions and the genius of this man will"|FALSE
1|"see nothing, or little, which can be attributed to fortune, inasmuch as"|FALSE
1|"he attained pre-eminence, as is shown above, not by the favour of any"|FALSE
1|"one, but step by step in the military profession, which steps were"|FALSE
1|"gained with a thousand troubles and perils, and were afterwards boldly"|FALSE
1|"held by him with many hazardous dangers. Yet it cannot be called talent"|FALSE
