1|"Hence it is to be remarked that, in seizing a state, the usurper ought"|FALSE
1|"to examine closely into all those injuries which it is necessary for him"|FALSE
1|"to inflict, and to do them all at one stroke so as not to have to repeat"|FALSE
1|"them daily; and thus by not unsettling men he will be able to reassure"|FALSE
1|"them, and win them to himself by benefits. He who does otherwise, either"|FALSE
1|"from timidity or evil advice, is always compelled to keep the knife"|FALSE
1|"in his hand; neither can he rely on his subjects, nor can they attach"|FALSE
1|"themselves to him, owing to their continued and repeated wrongs. For"|FALSE
1|"injuries ought to be done all at one time, so that, being tasted less,"|FALSE
1|"they offend less; benefits ought to be given little by little, so that"|FALSE
1|"the flavour of them may last longer."|FALSE
1|"And above all things, a prince ought to live amongst his people in such"|FALSE
1|"a way that no unexpected circumstances, whether of good or evil, shall"|FALSE
1|"make him change; because if the necessity for this comes in troubled"|FALSE
1|"times, you are too late for harsh measures; and mild ones will not help"|FALSE
1|"you, for they will be considered as forced from you, and no one will be"|FALSE
1|"under any obligation to you for them."|FALSE
1|"CHAPTER IX -- CONCERNING A CIVIL PRINCIPALITY"|FALSE
1|"But coming to the other point--where a leading citizen becomes the"|FALSE
1|"prince of his country, not by wickedness or any intolerable violence,"|FALSE
1|"but by the favour of his fellow citizens--this may be called a civil"|FALSE
1|"principality: nor is genius or fortune altogether necessary to attain to"|FALSE
1|"it, but rather a happy shrewdness. I say then that such a principality"|FALSE
1|"is obtained either by the favour of the people or by the favour of the"|FALSE
1|"nobles. Because in all cities these two distinct parties are found,"|FALSE
1|"and from this it arises that the people do not wish to be ruled nor"|FALSE
1|"oppressed by the nobles, and the nobles wish to rule and oppress the"|FALSE
1|"people; and from these two opposite desires there arises in cities one"|FALSE
1|"of three results, either a principality, self-government, or anarchy."|FALSE
1|"A principality is created either by the people or by the nobles,"|FALSE
1|"accordingly as one or other of them has the opportunity; for the nobles,"|FALSE
1|"seeing they cannot withstand the people, begin to cry up the reputation"|FALSE
1|"of one of themselves, and they make him a prince, so that under his"|FALSE
1|"shadow they can give vent to their ambitions. The people, finding"|FALSE
1|"they cannot resist the nobles, also cry up the reputation of one of"|FALSE
1|"themselves, and make him a prince so as to be defended by his authority."|FALSE
1|"He who obtains sovereignty by the assistance of the nobles maintains"|FALSE
1|"himself with more difficulty than he who comes to it by the aid of"|FALSE
1|"the people, because the former finds himself with many around him who"|FALSE
1|"consider themselves his equals, and because of this he can neither rule"|FALSE
1|"nor manage them to his liking. But he who reaches sovereignty by popular"|FALSE
1|"favour finds himself alone, and has none around him, or few, who are not"|FALSE
1|"prepared to obey him."|FALSE
1|"Besides this, one cannot by fair dealing, and without injury to others,"|FALSE
1|"satisfy the nobles, but you can satisfy the people, for their object is"|FALSE
1|"more righteous than that of the nobles, the latter wishing to oppress,"|FALSE
1|"while the former only desire not to be oppressed. It is to be added also"|FALSE
1|"that a prince can never secure himself against a hostile people, because"|FALSE
1|"of their being too many, whilst from the nobles he can secure himself,"|FALSE
1|"as they are few in number. The worst that a prince may expect from a"|FALSE
1|"hostile people is to be abandoned by them; but from hostile nobles he"|FALSE
1|"has not only to fear abandonment, but also that they will rise against"|FALSE
1|"him; for they, being in these affairs more far-seeing and astute, always"|FALSE
1|"come forward in time to save themselves, and to obtain favours from him"|FALSE
1|"whom they expect to prevail. Further, the prince is compelled to live"|FALSE
1|"always with the same people, but he can do well without the same nobles,"|FALSE
1|"being able to make and unmake them daily, and to give or take away"|FALSE
1|"authority when it pleases him."|FALSE
1|"Therefore, to make this point clearer, I say that the nobles ought to"|FALSE
1|"be looked at mainly in two ways: that is to say, they either shape their"|FALSE
1|"course in such a way as binds them entirely to your fortune, or they do"|FALSE
1|"not. Those who so bind themselves, and are not rapacious, ought to be"|FALSE
1|"honoured and loved; those who do not bind themselves may be dealt"|FALSE
1|"with in two ways; they may fail to do this through pusillanimity and a"|FALSE
1|"natural want of courage, in which case you ought to make use of them,"|FALSE
1|"especially of those who are of good counsel; and thus, whilst in"|FALSE
1|"prosperity you honour them, in adversity you do not have to fear them."|FALSE
1|"But when for their own ambitious ends they shun binding themselves, it"|FALSE
1|"is a token that they are giving more thought to themselves than to you,"|FALSE
1|"and a prince ought to guard against such, and to fear them as if they"|FALSE
1|"were open enemies, because in adversity they always help to ruin him."|FALSE
1|"Therefore, one who becomes a prince through the favour of the people"|FALSE
1|"ought to keep them friendly, and this he can easily do seeing they"|FALSE
1|"only ask not to be oppressed by him. But one who, in opposition to"|FALSE
1|"the people, becomes a prince by the favour of the nobles, ought, above"|FALSE
1|"everything, to seek to win the people over to himself, and this he may"|FALSE
1|"easily do if he takes them under his protection. Because men, when they"|FALSE
1|"receive good from him of whom they were expecting evil, are bound more"|FALSE
1|"closely to their benefactor; thus the people quickly become more devoted"|FALSE
1|"to him than if he had been raised to the principality by their favours;"|FALSE
1|"and the prince can win their affections in many ways, but as these vary"|FALSE
1|"according to the circumstances one cannot give fixed rules, so I omit"|FALSE
1|"them; but, I repeat, it is necessary for a prince to have the people"|FALSE
1|"friendly, otherwise he has no security in adversity."|FALSE
1|"Nabis,(*) Prince of the Spartans, sustained the attack of all Greece,"|FALSE
1|"and of a victorious Roman army, and against them he defended his country"|FALSE
1|"and his government; and for the overcoming of this peril it was only"|FALSE
1|"necessary for him to make himself secure against a few, but this would"|FALSE
1|"not have been sufficient had the people been hostile. And do not let any"|FALSE
