1|"These principalities are liable to danger when they are passing from the"|FALSE
1|"civil to the absolute order of government, for such princes either rule"|FALSE
1|"personally or through magistrates. In the latter case their government"|FALSE
1|"is weaker and more insecure, because it rests entirely on the goodwill"|FALSE
1|"of those citizens who are raised to the magistracy, and who, especially"|FALSE
1|"in troubled times, can destroy the government with great ease, either"|FALSE
1|"by intrigue or open defiance; and the prince has not the chance amid"|FALSE
1|"tumults to exercise absolute authority, because the citizens and"|FALSE
1|"subjects, accustomed to receive orders from magistrates, are not of"|FALSE
1|"a mind to obey him amid these confusions, and there will always be in"|FALSE
1|"doubtful times a scarcity of men whom he can trust. For such a prince"|FALSE
1|"cannot rely upon what he observes in quiet times, when citizens have"|FALSE
1|"need of the state, because then every one agrees with him; they all"|FALSE
1|"promise, and when death is far distant they all wish to die for him;"|FALSE
1|"but in troubled times, when the state has need of its citizens, then"|FALSE
1|"he finds but few. And so much the more is this experiment dangerous,"|FALSE
1|"inasmuch as it can only be tried once. Therefore a wise prince ought to"|FALSE
1|"adopt such a course that his citizens will always in every sort and"|FALSE
1|"kind of circumstance have need of the state and of him, and then he will"|FALSE
