1|"CHAPTER X -- CONCERNING THE WAY IN WHICH THE STRENGTH OF ALL"|FALSE
1|"PRINCIPALITIES OUGHT TO BE MEASURED"|FALSE
1|"It is necessary to consider another point in examining the character of"|FALSE
1|"these principalities: that is, whether a prince has such power that, in"|FALSE
1|"case of need, he can support himself with his own resources, or whether"|FALSE
1|"he has always need of the assistance of others. And to make this quite"|FALSE
1|"clear I say that I consider those who are able to support themselves by"|FALSE
1|"their own resources who can, either by abundance of men or money, raise"|FALSE
1|"a sufficient army to join battle against any one who comes to attack"|FALSE
1|"them; and I consider those always to have need of others who cannot"|FALSE
1|"show themselves against the enemy in the field, but are forced to"|FALSE
1|"defend themselves by sheltering behind walls. The first case has been"|FALSE
1|"discussed, but we will speak of it again should it recur. In the second"|FALSE
1|"case one can say nothing except to encourage such princes to provision"|FALSE
1|"and fortify their towns, and not on any account to defend the country."|FALSE
1|"And whoever shall fortify his town well, and shall have managed the"|FALSE
1|"other concerns of his subjects in the way stated above, and to be often"|FALSE
1|"repeated, will never be attacked without great caution, for men are"|FALSE
1|"always adverse to enterprises where difficulties can be seen, and it"|FALSE
1|"will be seen not to be an easy thing to attack one who has his town well"|FALSE
1|"fortified, and is not hated by his people."|FALSE
1|"The cities of Germany are absolutely free, they own but little country"|FALSE
1|"around them, and they yield obedience to the emperor when it suits"|FALSE
1|"them, nor do they fear this or any other power they may have near them,"|FALSE
1|"because they are fortified in such a way that every one thinks the"|FALSE
1|"taking of them by assault would be tedious and difficult, seeing they"|FALSE
1|"have proper ditches and walls, they have sufficient artillery, and they"|FALSE
1|"always keep in public depots enough for one year's eating, drinking, and"|FALSE
1|"firing. And beyond this, to keep the people quiet and without loss to"|FALSE
1|"the state, they always have the means of giving work to the community"|FALSE
1|"in those labours that are the life and strength of the city, and on"|FALSE
1|"the pursuit of which the people are supported; they also hold military"|FALSE
1|"exercises in repute, and moreover have many ordinances to uphold them."|FALSE
1|"Therefore, a prince who has a strong city, and had not made himself"|FALSE
1|"odious, will not be attacked, or if any one should attack he will only"|FALSE
1|"be driven off with disgrace; again, because that the affairs of this"|FALSE
1|"world are so changeable, it is almost impossible to keep an army a whole"|FALSE
1|"year in the field without being interfered with. And whoever should"|FALSE
1|"reply: If the people have property outside the city, and see it burnt,"|FALSE
1|"they will not remain patient, and the long siege and self-interest will"|FALSE
1|"make them forget their prince; to this I answer that a powerful and"|FALSE
1|"courageous prince will overcome all such difficulties by giving at one"|FALSE
1|"time hope to his subjects that the evil will not be for long, at another"|FALSE
1|"time fear of the cruelty of the enemy, then preserving himself adroitly"|FALSE
1|"from those subjects who seem to him to be too bold."|FALSE
1|"Further, the enemy would naturally on his arrival at once burn and ruin"|FALSE
1|"the country at the time when the spirits of the people are still hot and"|FALSE
1|"ready for the defence; and, therefore, so much the less ought the prince"|FALSE
1|"to hesitate; because after a time, when spirits have cooled, the damage"|FALSE
1|"is already done, the ills are incurred, and there is no longer any"|FALSE
1|"remedy; and therefore they are so much the more ready to unite with"|FALSE
1|"their prince, he appearing to be under obligations to them now that"|FALSE
1|"their houses have been burnt and their possessions ruined in his"|FALSE
1|"defence. For it is the nature of men to be bound by the benefits they"|FALSE
1|"confer as much as by those they receive. Therefore, if everything is"|FALSE
1|"well considered, it will not be difficult for a wise prince to keep the"|FALSE
1|"minds of his citizens steadfast from first to last, when he does not"|FALSE
1|"fail to support and defend them."|FALSE
1|"CHAPTER XI -- CONCERNING ECCLESIASTICAL PRINCIPALITIES"|FALSE
1|"It only remains now to speak of ecclesiastical principalities, touching"|FALSE
1|"which all difficulties are prior to getting possession, because they"|FALSE
1|"are acquired either by capacity or good fortune, and they can be held"|FALSE
1|"without either; for they are sustained by the ancient ordinances of"|FALSE
1|"religion, which are so all-powerful, and of such a character that the"|FALSE
1|"principalities may be held no matter how their princes behave and live."|FALSE
1|"These princes alone have states and do not defend them; and they have"|FALSE
1|"subjects and do not rule them; and the states, although unguarded, are"|FALSE
1|"not taken from them, and the subjects, although not ruled, do not care,"|FALSE
1|"and they have neither the desire nor the ability to alienate themselves."|FALSE
1|"Such principalities only are secure and happy. But being upheld by"|FALSE
1|"powers, to which the human mind cannot reach, I shall speak no more of"|FALSE
1|"them, because, being exalted and maintained by God, it would be the act"|FALSE
1|"of a presumptuous and rash man to discuss them."|FALSE
1|"Nevertheless, if any one should ask of me how comes it that the"|FALSE
1|"Church has attained such greatness in temporal power, seeing that from"|FALSE
1|"Alexander backwards the Italian potentates (not only those who have been"|FALSE
1|"called potentates, but every baron and lord, though the smallest)"|FALSE
1|"have valued the temporal power very slightly--yet now a king of France"|FALSE
1|"trembles before it, and it has been able to drive him from Italy, and"|FALSE
1|"to ruin the Venetians--although this may be very manifest, it does not"|FALSE
1|"appear to me superfluous to recall it in some measure to memory."|FALSE
1|"Before Charles, King of France, passed into Italy,(*) this country was"|FALSE
