1|"CHAPTER XII -- HOW MANY KINDS OF SOLDIERY THERE ARE, AND CONCERNING"|FALSE
1|"MERCENARIES"|FALSE
1|"Having discoursed particularly on the characteristics of such"|FALSE
1|"principalities as in the beginning I proposed to discuss, and having"|FALSE
1|"considered in some degree the causes of their being good or bad, and"|FALSE
1|"having shown the methods by which many have sought to acquire them and"|FALSE
1|"to hold them, it now remains for me to discuss generally the means of"|FALSE
1|"offence and defence which belong to each of them."|FALSE
1|"We have seen above how necessary it is for a prince to have his"|FALSE
1|"foundations well laid, otherwise it follows of necessity he will go"|FALSE
1|"to ruin. The chief foundations of all states, new as well as old or"|FALSE
1|"composite, are good laws and good arms; and as there cannot be good laws"|FALSE
1|"where the state is not well armed, it follows that where they are well"|FALSE
1|"armed they have good laws. I shall leave the laws out of the discussion"|FALSE
1|"and shall speak of the arms."|FALSE
1|"I say, therefore, that the arms with which a prince defends his state"|FALSE
1|"are either his own, or they are mercenaries, auxiliaries, or mixed."|FALSE
1|"Mercenaries and auxiliaries are useless and dangerous; and if one holds"|FALSE
1|"his state based on these arms, he will stand neither firm nor safe;"|FALSE
1|"for they are disunited, ambitious, and without discipline, unfaithful,"|FALSE
1|"valiant before friends, cowardly before enemies; they have neither the"|FALSE
1|"fear of God nor fidelity to men, and destruction is deferred only so"|FALSE
1|"long as the attack is; for in peace one is robbed by them, and in war"|FALSE
1|"by the enemy. The fact is, they have no other attraction or reason for"|FALSE
1|"keeping the field than a trifle of stipend, which is not sufficient"|FALSE
1|"to make them willing to die for you. They are ready enough to be"|FALSE
1|"your soldiers whilst you do not make war, but if war comes they take"|FALSE
1|"themselves off or run from the foe; which I should have little trouble"|FALSE
1|"to prove, for the ruin of Italy has been caused by nothing else than by"|FALSE
1|"resting all her hopes for many years on mercenaries, and although they"|FALSE
1|"formerly made some display and appeared valiant amongst themselves, yet"|FALSE
1|"when the foreigners came they showed what they were. Thus it was that"|FALSE
1|"Charles, King of France, was allowed to seize Italy with chalk in"|FALSE
1|"hand;(*) and he who told us that our sins were the cause of it told the"|FALSE
1|"truth, but they were not the sins he imagined, but those which I have"|FALSE
1|"related. And as they were the sins of princes, it is the princes who"|FALSE
1|"have also suffered the penalty."|FALSE
1|"     (*) \"With chalk in hand,\" \"col gesso.\" This is one of the"|FALSE
1|"     _bons mots_ of Alexander VI, and refers to the ease with"|FALSE
