1|"     History of Henry VII,\" by Lord Bacon: \"King Charles had"|FALSE
1|"     conquered the realm of Naples, and lost it again, in a kind"|FALSE
1|"     of a felicity of a dream. He passed the whole length of"|FALSE
1|"     Italy without resistance: so that it was true what Pope"|FALSE
1|"     Alexander was wont to say: That the Frenchmen came into"|FALSE
1|"     Italy with chalk in their hands, to mark up their lodgings,"|FALSE
1|"     rather than with swords to fight.\""|FALSE
1|"I wish to demonstrate further the infelicity of these arms. The"|FALSE
1|"mercenary captains are either capable men or they are not; if they"|FALSE
1|"are, you cannot trust them, because they always aspire to their own"|FALSE
1|"greatness, either by oppressing you, who are their master, or others"|FALSE
1|"contrary to your intentions; but if the captain is not skilful, you are"|FALSE
1|"ruined in the usual way."|FALSE
1|"And if it be urged that whoever is armed will act in the same way,"|FALSE
1|"whether mercenary or not, I reply that when arms have to be resorted to,"|FALSE
1|"either by a prince or a republic, then the prince ought to go in"|FALSE
1|"person and perform the duty of a captain; the republic has to send its"|FALSE
1|"citizens, and when one is sent who does not turn out satisfactorily, it"|FALSE
1|"ought to recall him, and when one is worthy, to hold him by the laws so"|FALSE
1|"that he does not leave the command. And experience has shown princes and"|FALSE
1|"republics, single-handed, making the greatest progress, and mercenaries"|FALSE
1|"doing nothing except damage; and it is more difficult to bring a"|FALSE
1|"republic, armed with its own arms, under the sway of one of its citizens"|FALSE
1|"than it is to bring one armed with foreign arms. Rome and Sparta stood"|FALSE
1|"for many ages armed and free. The Switzers are completely armed and"|FALSE
1|"quite free."|FALSE
1|"Of ancient mercenaries, for example, there are the Carthaginians, who"|FALSE
