1|"And as with these examples I have reached Italy, which has been ruled"|FALSE
1|"for many years by mercenaries, I wish to discuss them more seriously,"|FALSE
1|"in order that, having seen their rise and progress, one may be better"|FALSE
1|"prepared to counteract them. You must understand that the empire has"|FALSE
1|"recently come to be repudiated in Italy, that the Pope has acquired more"|FALSE
1|"temporal power, and that Italy has been divided up into more states,"|FALSE
1|"for the reason that many of the great cities took up arms against their"|FALSE
1|"nobles, who, formerly favoured by the emperor, were oppressing them,"|FALSE
1|"whilst the Church was favouring them so as to gain authority in temporal"|FALSE
1|"power: in many others their citizens became princes. From this it came"|FALSE
1|"to pass that Italy fell partly into the hands of the Church and of"|FALSE
1|"republics, and, the Church consisting of priests and the republic of"|FALSE
1|"citizens unaccustomed to arms, both commenced to enlist foreigners."|FALSE
1|"The first who gave renown to this soldiery was Alberigo da Conio,(*) the"|FALSE
1|"Romagnian. From the school of this man sprang, among others, Braccio and"|FALSE
1|"Sforza, who in their time were the arbiters of Italy. After these came"|FALSE
1|"all the other captains who till now have directed the arms of Italy;"|FALSE
1|"and the end of all their valour has been, that she has been overrun"|FALSE
1|"by Charles, robbed by Louis, ravaged by Ferdinand, and insulted by the"|FALSE
1|"Switzers. The principle that has guided them has been, first, to lower"|FALSE
1|"the credit of infantry so that they might increase their own. They did"|FALSE
1|"this because, subsisting on their pay and without territory, they were"|FALSE
1|"unable to support many soldiers, and a few infantry did not give them"|FALSE
1|"any authority; so they were led to employ cavalry, with a moderate force"|FALSE
1|"of which they were maintained and honoured; and affairs were brought to"|FALSE
1|"such a pass that, in an army of twenty thousand soldiers, there were"|FALSE
1|"not to be found two thousand foot soldiers. They had, besides this, used"|FALSE
1|"every art to lessen fatigue and danger to themselves and their soldiers,"|FALSE
1|"not killing in the fray, but taking prisoners and liberating without"|FALSE
1|"ransom. They did not attack towns at night, nor did the garrisons of the"|FALSE
1|"towns attack encampments at night; they did not surround the camp either"|FALSE
1|"with stockade or ditch, nor did they campaign in the winter. All these"|FALSE
1|"things were permitted by their military rules, and devised by them to"|FALSE
1|"avoid, as I have said, both fatigue and dangers; thus they have brought"|FALSE
1|"Italy to slavery and contempt."|FALSE
