1|"CHAPTER XIII -- CONCERNING AUXILIARIES, MIXED SOLDIERY, AND ONE'S OWN"|FALSE
1|"Auxiliaries, which are the other useless arm, are employed when a prince"|FALSE
1|"is called in with his forces to aid and defend, as was done by Pope"|FALSE
1|"Julius in the most recent times; for he, having, in the enterprise"|FALSE
1|"against Ferrara, had poor proof of his mercenaries, turned to"|FALSE
1|"auxiliaries, and stipulated with Ferdinand, King of Spain,(*) for his"|FALSE
1|"assistance with men and arms. These arms may be useful and good"|FALSE
1|"in themselves, but for him who calls them in they are always"|FALSE
1|"disadvantageous; for losing, one is undone, and winning, one is their"|FALSE
1|"captive."|FALSE
1|"     (*) Ferdinand V (F. II of Aragon and Sicily, F. III of"|FALSE
1|"     Naples), surnamed \"The Catholic,\" born 1542, died 1516."|FALSE
1|"And although ancient histories may be full of examples, I do not wish"|FALSE
1|"to leave this recent one of Pope Julius the Second, the peril of which"|FALSE
1|"cannot fail to be perceived; for he, wishing to get Ferrara, threw"|FALSE
1|"himself entirely into the hands of the foreigner. But his good fortune"|FALSE
1|"brought about a third event, so that he did not reap the fruit of his"|FALSE
1|"rash choice; because, having his auxiliaries routed at Ravenna, and"|FALSE
1|"the Switzers having risen and driven out the conquerors (against all"|FALSE
1|"expectation, both his and others), it so came to pass that he did"|FALSE
1|"not become prisoner to his enemies, they having fled, nor to his"|FALSE
1|"auxiliaries, he having conquered by other arms than theirs."|FALSE
1|"The Florentines, being entirely without arms, sent ten thousand"|FALSE
1|"Frenchmen to take Pisa, whereby they ran more danger than at any other"|FALSE
1|"time of their troubles."|FALSE
1|"The Emperor of Constantinople,(*) to oppose his neighbours, sent ten"|FALSE
1|"thousand Turks into Greece, who, on the war being finished, were not"|FALSE
1|"willing to quit; this was the beginning of the servitude of Greece to"|FALSE
1|"the infidels."|FALSE
1|"     (*) Joannes Cantacuzenus, born 1300, died 1383."|FALSE
1|"Therefore, let him who has no desire to conquer make use of these arms,"|FALSE
1|"for they are much more hazardous than mercenaries, because with them the"|FALSE
1|"ruin is ready made; they are all united, all yield obedience to others;"|FALSE
1|"but with mercenaries, when they have conquered, more time and better"|FALSE
1|"opportunities are needed to injure you; they are not all of one"|FALSE
1|"community, they are found and paid by you, and a third party, which you"|FALSE
1|"have made their head, is not able all at once to assume enough authority"|FALSE
1|"to injure you. In conclusion, in mercenaries dastardy is most dangerous;"|FALSE
1|"in auxiliaries, valour. The wise prince, therefore, has always avoided"|FALSE
1|"these arms and turned to his own; and has been willing rather to lose"|FALSE
1|"with them than to conquer with the others, not deeming that a real"|FALSE
1|"victory which is gained with the arms of others."|FALSE
1|"I shall never hesitate to cite Cesare Borgia and his actions. This duke"|FALSE
1|"entered the Romagna with auxiliaries, taking there only French soldiers,"|FALSE
1|"and with them he captured Imola and Forli; but afterwards, such forces"|FALSE
1|"not appearing to him reliable, he turned to mercenaries, discerning less"|FALSE
1|"danger in them, and enlisted the Orsini and Vitelli; whom presently,"|FALSE
1|"on handling and finding them doubtful, unfaithful, and dangerous, he"|FALSE
1|"destroyed and turned to his own men. And the difference between one"|FALSE
1|"and the other of these forces can easily be seen when one considers"|FALSE
1|"the difference there was in the reputation of the duke, when he had the"|FALSE
1|"French, when he had the Orsini and Vitelli, and when he relied on his"|FALSE
1|"own soldiers, on whose fidelity he could always count and found it ever"|FALSE
1|"increasing; he was never esteemed more highly than when every one saw"|FALSE
1|"that he was complete master of his own forces."|FALSE
1|"I was not intending to go beyond Italian and recent examples, but I am"|FALSE
1|"unwilling to leave out Hiero, the Syracusan, he being one of those I"|FALSE
1|"have named above. This man, as I have said, made head of the army by the"|FALSE
1|"Syracusans, soon found out that a mercenary soldiery, constituted like"|FALSE
1|"our Italian condottieri, was of no use; and it appearing to him that he"|FALSE
1|"could neither keep them not let them go, he had them all cut to pieces,"|FALSE
1|"and afterwards made war with his own forces and not with aliens."|FALSE
1|"I wish also to recall to memory an instance from the Old Testament"|FALSE
1|"applicable to this subject. David offered himself to Saul to fight with"|FALSE
1|"Goliath, the Philistine champion, and, to give him courage, Saul armed"|FALSE
1|"him with his own weapons; which David rejected as soon as he had them"|FALSE
1|"on his back, saying he could make no use of them, and that he wished to"|FALSE
1|"meet the enemy with his sling and his knife. In conclusion, the arms of"|FALSE
1|"others either fall from your back, or they weigh you down, or they bind"|FALSE
1|"you fast."|FALSE
1|"Charles the Seventh,(*) the father of King Louis the Eleventh,(+) having"|FALSE
1|"by good fortune and valour liberated France from the English, recognized"|FALSE
1|"the necessity of being armed with forces of his own, and he established"|FALSE
1|"in his kingdom ordinances concerning men-at-arms and infantry."|FALSE
1|"Afterwards his son, King Louis, abolished the infantry and began to"|FALSE
1|"enlist the Switzers, which mistake, followed by others, is, as is now"|FALSE
1|"seen, a source of peril to that kingdom; because, having raised the"|FALSE
