1|"I conclude, therefore, that no principality is secure without having its"|FALSE
1|"own forces; on the contrary, it is entirely dependent on good fortune,"|FALSE
1|"not having the valour which in adversity would defend it. And it has"|FALSE
1|"always been the opinion and judgment of wise men that nothing can be so"|FALSE
1|"uncertain or unstable as fame or power not founded on its own strength."|FALSE
1|"And one's own forces are those which are composed either of subjects,"|FALSE
1|"citizens, or dependents; all others are mercenaries or auxiliaries. And"|FALSE
1|"the way to make ready one's own forces will be easily found if the rules"|FALSE
1|"suggested by me shall be reflected upon, and if one will consider"|FALSE
1|"how Philip, the father of Alexander the Great, and many republics and"|FALSE
