1|"CHAPTER XIV -- THAT WHICH CONCERNS A PRINCE ON THE SUBJECT OF THE ART OF"|FALSE
1|"WAR"|FALSE
1|"A prince ought to have no other aim or thought, nor select anything else"|FALSE
1|"for his study, than war and its rules and discipline; for this is the"|FALSE
1|"sole art that belongs to him who rules, and it is of such force that it"|FALSE
1|"not only upholds those who are born princes, but it often enables men"|FALSE
1|"to rise from a private station to that rank. And, on the contrary, it is"|FALSE
1|"seen that when princes have thought more of ease than of arms they have"|FALSE
1|"lost their states. And the first cause of your losing it is to neglect"|FALSE
1|"this art; and what enables you to acquire a state is to be master of"|FALSE
1|"the art. Francesco Sforza, through being martial, from a private person"|FALSE
1|"became Duke of Milan; and the sons, through avoiding the hardships and"|FALSE
1|"troubles of arms, from dukes became private persons. For among other"|FALSE
1|"evils which being unarmed brings you, it causes you to be despised, and"|FALSE
1|"this is one of those ignominies against which a prince ought to guard"|FALSE
1|"himself, as is shown later on. Because there is nothing proportionate"|FALSE
1|"between the armed and the unarmed; and it is not reasonable that he who"|FALSE
1|"is armed should yield obedience willingly to him who is unarmed, or that"|FALSE
1|"the unarmed man should be secure among armed servants. Because, there"|FALSE
1|"being in the one disdain and in the other suspicion, it is not possible"|FALSE
1|"for them to work well together. And therefore a prince who does not"|FALSE
1|"understand the art of war, over and above the other misfortunes already"|FALSE
1|"mentioned, cannot be respected by his soldiers, nor can he rely on them."|FALSE
1|"He ought never, therefore, to have out of his thoughts this subject of"|FALSE
1|"war, and in peace he should addict himself more to its exercise than in"|FALSE
1|"war; this he can do in two ways, the one by action, the other by study."|FALSE
1|"As regards action, he ought above all things to keep his men well"|FALSE
1|"organized and drilled, to follow incessantly the chase, by which he"|FALSE
1|"accustoms his body to hardships, and learns something of the nature of"|FALSE
1|"localities, and gets to find out how the mountains rise, how the valleys"|FALSE
1|"open out, how the plains lie, and to understand the nature of rivers and"|FALSE
