1|"CHAPTER XV -- CONCERNING THINGS FOR WHICH MEN, AND ESPECIALLY PRINCES,"|FALSE
1|"ARE PRAISED OR BLAMED"|FALSE
1|"It remains now to see what ought to be the rules of conduct for a prince"|FALSE
1|"towards subject and friends. And as I know that many have written on"|FALSE
1|"this point, I expect I shall be considered presumptuous in mentioning it"|FALSE
1|"again, especially as in discussing it I shall depart from the methods of"|FALSE
1|"other people. But, it being my intention to write a thing which shall"|FALSE
1|"be useful to him who apprehends it, it appears to me more appropriate to"|FALSE
1|"follow up the real truth of the matter than the imagination of it; for"|FALSE
1|"many have pictured republics and principalities which in fact have never"|FALSE
1|"been known or seen, because how one lives is so far distant from how one"|FALSE
1|"ought to live, that he who neglects what is done for what ought to"|FALSE
1|"be done, sooner effects his ruin than his preservation; for a man who"|FALSE
1|"wishes to act entirely up to his professions of virtue soon meets with"|FALSE
1|"what destroys him among so much that is evil."|FALSE
1|"Hence it is necessary for a prince wishing to hold his own to know"|FALSE
1|"how to do wrong, and to make use of it or not according to necessity."|FALSE
1|"Therefore, putting on one side imaginary things concerning a prince, and"|FALSE
1|"discussing those which are real, I say that all men when they are spoken"|FALSE
1|"of, and chiefly princes for being more highly placed, are remarkable"|FALSE
1|"for some of those qualities which bring them either blame or praise; and"|FALSE
1|"thus it is that one is reputed liberal, another miserly, using a Tuscan"|FALSE
1|"term (because an avaricious person in our language is still he who"|FALSE
1|"desires to possess by robbery, whilst we call one miserly who deprives"|FALSE
1|"himself too much of the use of his own); one is reputed generous,"|FALSE
1|"one rapacious; one cruel, one compassionate; one faithless, another"|FALSE
1|"faithful; one effeminate and cowardly, another bold and brave; one"|FALSE
1|"affable, another haughty; one lascivious, another chaste; one sincere,"|FALSE
1|"another cunning; one hard, another easy; one grave, another frivolous;"|FALSE
1|"one religious, another unbelieving, and the like. And I know that every"|FALSE
1|"one will confess that it would be most praiseworthy in a prince to"|FALSE
1|"exhibit all the above qualities that are considered good; but because"|FALSE
1|"they can neither be entirely possessed nor observed, for human"|FALSE
1|"conditions do not permit it, it is necessary for him to be sufficiently"|FALSE
1|"prudent that he may know how to avoid the reproach of those vices which"|FALSE
1|"would lose him his state; and also to keep himself, if it be possible,"|FALSE
1|"from those which would not lose him it; but this not being possible, he"|FALSE
1|"may with less hesitation abandon himself to them. And again, he need"|FALSE
1|"not make himself uneasy at incurring a reproach for those vices without"|FALSE
1|"which the state can only be saved with difficulty, for if everything is"|FALSE
1|"considered carefully, it will be found that something which looks like"|FALSE
1|"virtue, if followed, would be his ruin; whilst something else, which"|FALSE
1|"looks like vice, yet followed brings him security and prosperity."|FALSE
1|"CHAPTER XVI -- CONCERNING LIBERALITY AND MEANNESS"|FALSE
1|"Commencing then with the first of the above-named characteristics, I say"|FALSE
1|"that it would be well to be reputed liberal. Nevertheless, liberality"|FALSE
1|"exercised in a way that does not bring you the reputation for it,"|FALSE
1|"injures you; for if one exercises it honestly and as it should be"|FALSE
1|"exercised, it may not become known, and you will not avoid the reproach"|FALSE
1|"of its opposite. Therefore, any one wishing to maintain among men the"|FALSE
1|"name of liberal is obliged to avoid no attribute of magnificence; so"|FALSE
1|"that a prince thus inclined will consume in such acts all his property,"|FALSE
1|"and will be compelled in the end, if he wish to maintain the name"|FALSE
1|"of liberal, to unduly weigh down his people, and tax them, and do"|FALSE
1|"everything he can to get money. This will soon make him odious to his"|FALSE
1|"subjects, and becoming poor he will be little valued by any one; thus,"|FALSE
1|"with his liberality, having offended many and rewarded few, he is"|FALSE
1|"affected by the very first trouble and imperilled by whatever may be the"|FALSE
1|"first danger; recognizing this himself, and wishing to draw back from"|FALSE
1|"it, he runs at once into the reproach of being miserly."|FALSE
1|"Therefore, a prince, not being able to exercise this virtue of"|FALSE
1|"liberality in such a way that it is recognized, except to his cost, if"|FALSE
1|"he is wise he ought not to fear the reputation of being mean, for in"|FALSE
1|"time he will come to be more considered than if liberal, seeing that"|FALSE
1|"with his economy his revenues are enough, that he can defend himself"|FALSE
1|"against all attacks, and is able to engage in enterprises without"|FALSE
1|"burdening his people; thus it comes to pass that he exercises liberality"|FALSE
1|"towards all from whom he does not take, who are numberless, and meanness"|FALSE
1|"towards those to whom he does not give, who are few."|FALSE
1|"We have not seen great things done in our time except by those who have"|FALSE
1|"been considered mean; the rest have failed. Pope Julius the Second was"|FALSE
1|"assisted in reaching the papacy by a reputation for liberality, yet he"|FALSE
1|"did not strive afterwards to keep it up, when he made war on the King of"|FALSE
1|"France; and he made many wars without imposing any extraordinary tax on"|FALSE
1|"his subjects, for he supplied his additional expenses out of his long"|FALSE
1|"thriftiness. The present King of Spain would not have undertaken or"|FALSE
1|"conquered in so many enterprises if he had been reputed liberal. A"|FALSE
1|"prince, therefore, provided that he has not to rob his subjects, that he"|FALSE
1|"can defend himself, that he does not become poor and abject, that he"|FALSE
1|"is not forced to become rapacious, ought to hold of little account"|FALSE
1|"a reputation for being mean, for it is one of those vices which will"|FALSE
1|"enable him to govern."|FALSE
1|"And if any one should say: Caesar obtained empire by liberality, and"|FALSE
1|"many others have reached the highest positions by having been liberal,"|FALSE
1|"and by being considered so, I answer: Either you are a prince in"|FALSE
1|"fact, or in a way to become one. In the first case this liberality is"|FALSE
1|"dangerous, in the second it is very necessary to be considered liberal;"|FALSE
1|"and Caesar was one of those who wished to become pre-eminent in Rome;"|FALSE
1|"but if he had survived after becoming so, and had not moderated his"|FALSE
1|"expenses, he would have destroyed his government. And if any one should"|FALSE
1|"reply: Many have been princes, and have done great things with armies,"|FALSE
1|"who have been considered very liberal, I reply: Either a prince spends"|FALSE
1|"that which is his own or his subjects' or else that of others. In the"|FALSE
1|"first case he ought to be sparing, in the second he ought not to neglect"|FALSE
1|"any opportunity for liberality. And to the prince who goes forth with"|FALSE
1|"his army, supporting it by pillage, sack, and extortion, handling that"|FALSE
1|"which belongs to others, this liberality is necessary, otherwise he"|FALSE
1|"would not be followed by soldiers. And of that which is neither yours"|FALSE
1|"nor your subjects' you can be a ready giver, as were Cyrus, Caesar, and"|FALSE
1|"Alexander; because it does not take away your reputation if you squander"|FALSE
1|"that of others, but adds to it; it is only squandering your own that"|FALSE
1|"injures you."|FALSE
1|"And there is nothing wastes so rapidly as liberality, for even whilst"|FALSE
1|"you exercise it you lose the power to do so, and so become either poor"|FALSE
1|"or despised, or else, in avoiding poverty, rapacious and hated. And a"|FALSE
1|"prince should guard himself, above all things, against being despised"|FALSE
1|"and hated; and liberality leads you to both. Therefore it is wiser to"|FALSE
1|"have a reputation for meanness which brings reproach without hatred,"|FALSE
1|"than to be compelled through seeking a reputation for liberality to"|FALSE
1|"incur a name for rapacity which begets reproach with hatred."|FALSE
1|"CHAPTER XVII -- CONCERNING CRUELTY AND CLEMENCY, AND WHETHER IT IS"|FALSE
1|"BETTER TO BE LOVED THAN FEARED"|FALSE
1|"Coming now to the other qualities mentioned above, I say that every"|FALSE
1|"prince ought to desire to be considered clement and not cruel."|FALSE
