1|"Upon this a question arises: whether it be better to be loved than"|FALSE
1|"feared or feared than loved? It may be answered that one should wish to"|FALSE
1|"be both, but, because it is difficult to unite them in one person, it"|FALSE
1|"is much safer to be feared than loved, when, of the two, either must be"|FALSE
1|"dispensed with. Because this is to be asserted in general of men, that"|FALSE
1|"they are ungrateful, fickle, false, cowardly, covetous, and as long as"|FALSE
1|"you succeed they are yours entirely; they will offer you their blood,"|FALSE
1|"property, life, and children, as is said above, when the need is far"|FALSE
1|"distant; but when it approaches they turn against you. And that"|FALSE
1|"prince who, relying entirely on their promises, has neglected other"|FALSE
1|"precautions, is ruined; because friendships that are obtained by"|FALSE
1|"payments, and not by greatness or nobility of mind, may indeed be"|FALSE
1|"earned, but they are not secured, and in time of need cannot be relied"|FALSE
1|"upon; and men have less scruple in offending one who is beloved than one"|FALSE
1|"who is feared, for love is preserved by the link of obligation which,"|FALSE
1|"owing to the baseness of men, is broken at every opportunity for their"|FALSE
1|"advantage; but fear preserves you by a dread of punishment which never"|FALSE
1|"fails."|FALSE
1|"Nevertheless a prince ought to inspire fear in such a way that, if he"|FALSE
1|"does not win love, he avoids hatred; because he can endure very well"|FALSE
1|"being feared whilst he is not hated, which will always be as long as he"|FALSE
1|"abstains from the property of his citizens and subjects and from their"|FALSE
1|"women. But when it is necessary for him to proceed against the life of"|FALSE
1|"someone, he must do it on proper justification and for manifest cause,"|FALSE
1|"but above all things he must keep his hands off the property of others,"|FALSE
1|"because men more quickly forget the death of their father than the loss"|FALSE
1|"of their patrimony. Besides, pretexts for taking away the property are"|FALSE
1|"never wanting; for he who has once begun to live by robbery will always"|FALSE
1|"find pretexts for seizing what belongs to others; but reasons for taking"|FALSE
1|"life, on the contrary, are more difficult to find and sooner lapse. But"|FALSE
1|"when a prince is with his army, and has under control a multitude of"|FALSE
1|"soldiers, then it is quite necessary for him to disregard the reputation"|FALSE
1|"of cruelty, for without it he would never hold his army united or"|FALSE
1|"disposed to its duties."|FALSE
1|"Among the wonderful deeds of Hannibal this one is enumerated: that"|FALSE
