1|"Every one admits how praiseworthy it is in a prince to keep faith, and"|FALSE
1|"to live with integrity and not with craft. Nevertheless our experience"|FALSE
1|"has been that those princes who have done great things have held good"|FALSE
1|"faith of little account, and have known how to circumvent the intellect"|FALSE
1|"of men by craft, and in the end have overcome those who have relied on"|FALSE
1|"their word. You must know there are two ways of contesting,(*) the one"|FALSE
1|"by the law, the other by force; the first method is proper to men, the"|FALSE
1|"second to beasts; but because the first is frequently not sufficient, it"|FALSE
1|"is necessary to have recourse to the second. Therefore it is necessary"|FALSE
1|"for a prince to understand how to avail himself of the beast and the"|FALSE
1|"man. This has been figuratively taught to princes by ancient writers,"|FALSE
1|"who describe how Achilles and many other princes of old were given to"|FALSE
1|"the Centaur Chiron to nurse, who brought them up in his discipline;"|FALSE
1|"which means solely that, as they had for a teacher one who was half"|FALSE
1|"beast and half man, so it is necessary for a prince to know how to make"|FALSE
1|"use of both natures, and that one without the other is not durable. A"|FALSE
1|"prince, therefore, being compelled knowingly to adopt the beast, ought"|FALSE
1|"to choose the fox and the lion; because the lion cannot defend himself"|FALSE
1|"against snares and the fox cannot defend himself against wolves."|FALSE
1|"Therefore, it is necessary to be a fox to discover the snares and a"|FALSE
1|"lion to terrify the wolves. Those who rely simply on the lion do not"|FALSE
1|"understand what they are about. Therefore a wise lord cannot, nor ought"|FALSE
1|"he to, keep faith when such observance may be turned against him, and"|FALSE
1|"when the reasons that caused him to pledge it exist no longer. If men"|FALSE
1|"were entirely good this precept would not hold, but because they are"|FALSE
1|"bad, and will not keep faith with you, you too are not bound to observe"|FALSE
1|"it with them. Nor will there ever be wanting to a prince legitimate"|FALSE
1|"reasons to excuse this non-observance. Of this endless modern examples"|FALSE
1|"could be given, showing how many treaties and engagements have been made"|FALSE
1|"void and of no effect through the faithlessness of princes; and he who"|FALSE
1|"has known best how to employ the fox has succeeded best."|FALSE
