1|"CHAPTER XXI -- HOW A PRINCE SHOULD CONDUCT HIMSELF SO AS TO GAIN RENOWN"|FALSE
1|"Nothing makes a prince so much esteemed as great enterprises and setting"|FALSE
1|"a fine example. We have in our time Ferdinand of Aragon, the present"|FALSE
1|"King of Spain. He can almost be called a new prince, because he has"|FALSE
1|"risen, by fame and glory, from being an insignificant king to be the"|FALSE
1|"foremost king in Christendom; and if you will consider his deeds"|FALSE
1|"you will find them all great and some of them extraordinary. In the"|FALSE
1|"beginning of his reign he attacked Granada, and this enterprise was the"|FALSE
1|"foundation of his dominions. He did this quietly at first and without"|FALSE
1|"any fear of hindrance, for he held the minds of the barons of Castile"|FALSE
1|"occupied in thinking of the war and not anticipating any innovations;"|FALSE
1|"thus they did not perceive that by these means he was acquiring power"|FALSE
1|"and authority over them. He was able with the money of the Church and"|FALSE
1|"of the people to sustain his armies, and by that long war to lay the"|FALSE
1|"foundation for the military skill which has since distinguished him."|FALSE
1|"Further, always using religion as a plea, so as to undertake greater"|FALSE
1|"schemes, he devoted himself with pious cruelty to driving out and"|FALSE
1|"clearing his kingdom of the Moors; nor could there be a more admirable"|FALSE
1|"example, nor one more rare. Under this same cloak he assailed Africa,"|FALSE
1|"he came down on Italy, he has finally attacked France; and thus his"|FALSE
1|"achievements and designs have always been great, and have kept the minds"|FALSE
1|"of his people in suspense and admiration and occupied with the issue of"|FALSE
1|"them. And his actions have arisen in such a way, one out of the other,"|FALSE
1|"that men have never been given time to work steadily against him."|FALSE
1|"Again, it much assists a prince to set unusual examples in internal"|FALSE
1|"affairs, similar to those which are related of Messer Bernabo da Milano,"|FALSE
1|"who, when he had the opportunity, by any one in civil life doing some"|FALSE
1|"extraordinary thing, either good or bad, would take some method of"|FALSE
1|"rewarding or punishing him, which would be much spoken about. And a"|FALSE
1|"prince ought, above all things, always endeavour in every action to gain"|FALSE
1|"for himself the reputation of being a great and remarkable man."|FALSE
1|"A prince is also respected when he is either a true friend or a"|FALSE
1|"downright enemy, that is to say, when, without any reservation, he"|FALSE
1|"declares himself in favour of one party against the other; which course"|FALSE
1|"will always be more advantageous than standing neutral; because if two"|FALSE
1|"of your powerful neighbours come to blows, they are of such a character"|FALSE
1|"that, if one of them conquers, you have either to fear him or not."|FALSE
1|"In either case it will always be more advantageous for you to declare"|FALSE
1|"yourself and to make war strenuously; because, in the first case, if"|FALSE
1|"you do not declare yourself, you will invariably fall a prey to"|FALSE
1|"the conqueror, to the pleasure and satisfaction of him who has been"|FALSE
1|"conquered, and you will have no reasons to offer, nor anything to"|FALSE
1|"protect or to shelter you. Because he who conquers does not want"|FALSE
1|"doubtful friends who will not aid him in the time of trial; and he who"|FALSE
1|"loses will not harbour you because you did not willingly, sword in hand,"|FALSE
1|"court his fate."|FALSE
1|"Antiochus went into Greece, being sent for by the Aetolians to drive"|FALSE
1|"out the Romans. He sent envoys to the Achaeans, who were friends of"|FALSE
1|"the Romans, exhorting them to remain neutral; and on the other hand the"|FALSE
1|"Romans urged them to take up arms. This question came to be discussed in"|FALSE
1|"the council of the Achaeans, where the legate of Antiochus urged them to"|FALSE
1|"stand neutral. To this the Roman legate answered: \"As for that which has"|FALSE
1|"been said, that it is better and more advantageous for your state not"|FALSE
1|"to interfere in our war, nothing can be more erroneous; because by"|FALSE
1|"not interfering you will be left, without favour or consideration, the"|FALSE
1|"guerdon of the conqueror.\" Thus it will always happen that he who is not"|FALSE
1|"your friend will demand your neutrality, whilst he who is your friend"|FALSE
1|"will entreat you to declare yourself with arms. And irresolute princes,"|FALSE
1|"to avoid present dangers, generally follow the neutral path, and are"|FALSE
1|"generally ruined. But when a prince declares himself gallantly in favour"|FALSE
1|"of one side, if the party with whom he allies himself conquers, although"|FALSE
1|"the victor may be powerful and may have him at his mercy, yet he is"|FALSE
1|"indebted to him, and there is established a bond of amity; and men are"|FALSE
1|"never so shameless as to become a monument of ingratitude by oppressing"|FALSE
1|"you. Victories after all are never so complete that the victor must not"|FALSE
1|"show some regard, especially to justice. But if he with whom you ally"|FALSE
1|"yourself loses, you may be sheltered by him, and whilst he is able he"|FALSE
1|"may aid you, and you become companions on a fortune that may rise again."|FALSE
1|"In the second case, when those who fight are of such a character that"|FALSE
1|"you have no anxiety as to who may conquer, so much the more is it"|FALSE
1|"greater prudence to be allied, because you assist at the destruction"|FALSE
1|"of one by the aid of another who, if he had been wise, would have saved"|FALSE
1|"him; and conquering, as it is impossible that he should not do with your"|FALSE
1|"assistance, he remains at your discretion. And here it is to be noted"|FALSE
1|"that a prince ought to take care never to make an alliance with one"|FALSE
1|"more powerful than himself for the purposes of attacking others, unless"|FALSE
1|"necessity compels him, as is said above; because if he conquers you are"|FALSE
1|"at his discretion, and princes ought to avoid as much as possible being"|FALSE
1|"at the discretion of any one. The Venetians joined with France against"|FALSE
1|"the Duke of Milan, and this alliance, which caused their ruin, could"|FALSE
1|"have been avoided. But when it cannot be avoided, as happened to the"|FALSE
1|"Florentines when the Pope and Spain sent armies to attack Lombardy, then"|FALSE
1|"in such a case, for the above reasons, the prince ought to favour one of"|FALSE
1|"the parties."|FALSE
1|"Never let any Government imagine that it can choose perfectly safe"|FALSE
1|"courses; rather let it expect to have to take very doubtful ones,"|FALSE
1|"because it is found in ordinary affairs that one never seeks to avoid"|FALSE
1|"one trouble without running into another; but prudence consists in"|FALSE
1|"knowing how to distinguish the character of troubles, and for choice to"|FALSE
1|"take the lesser evil."|FALSE
1|"A prince ought also to show himself a patron of ability, and to honour"|FALSE
1|"the proficient in every art. At the same time he should encourage his"|FALSE
1|"citizens to practise their callings peaceably, both in commerce and"|FALSE
