1|"CHAPTER XXII -- CONCERNING THE SECRETARIES OF PRINCES"|FALSE
1|"The choice of servants is of no little importance to a prince, and they"|FALSE
1|"are good or not according to the discrimination of the prince. And the"|FALSE
1|"first opinion which one forms of a prince, and of his understanding, is"|FALSE
1|"by observing the men he has around him; and when they are capable and"|FALSE
1|"faithful he may always be considered wise, because he has known how"|FALSE
1|"to recognize the capable and to keep them faithful. But when they are"|FALSE
1|"otherwise one cannot form a good opinion of him, for the prime error"|FALSE
1|"which he made was in choosing them."|FALSE
1|"There were none who knew Messer Antonio da Venafro as the servant of"|FALSE
1|"Pandolfo Petrucci, Prince of Siena, who would not consider Pandolfo to"|FALSE
1|"be a very clever man in having Venafro for his servant. Because there"|FALSE
1|"are three classes of intellects: one which comprehends by itself;"|FALSE
1|"another which appreciates what others comprehended; and a third which"|FALSE
1|"neither comprehends by itself nor by the showing of others; the first is"|FALSE
1|"the most excellent, the second is good, the third is useless. Therefore,"|FALSE
1|"it follows necessarily that, if Pandolfo was not in the first rank, he"|FALSE
1|"was in the second, for whenever one has judgment to know good and"|FALSE
1|"bad when it is said and done, although he himself may not have the"|FALSE
1|"initiative, yet he can recognize the good and the bad in his servant,"|FALSE
1|"and the one he can praise and the other correct; thus the servant cannot"|FALSE
1|"hope to deceive him, and is kept honest."|FALSE
1|"But to enable a prince to form an opinion of his servant there is one"|FALSE
1|"test which never fails; when you see the servant thinking more of his"|FALSE
1|"own interests than of yours, and seeking inwardly his own profit in"|FALSE
1|"everything, such a man will never make a good servant, nor will you ever"|FALSE
1|"be able to trust him; because he who has the state of another in his"|FALSE
1|"hands ought never to think of himself, but always of his prince, and"|FALSE
1|"never pay any attention to matters in which the prince is not concerned."|FALSE
1|"On the other hand, to keep his servant honest the prince ought to study"|FALSE
1|"him, honouring him, enriching him, doing him kindnesses, sharing with"|FALSE
1|"him the honours and cares; and at the same time let him see that he"|FALSE
1|"cannot stand alone, so that many honours may not make him desire more,"|FALSE
1|"many riches make him wish for more, and that many cares may make him"|FALSE
1|"dread chances. When, therefore, servants, and princes towards servants,"|FALSE
1|"are thus disposed, they can trust each other, but when it is otherwise,"|FALSE
1|"the end will always be disastrous for either one or the other."|FALSE
1|"CHAPTER XXIII -- HOW FLATTERERS SHOULD BE AVOIDED"|FALSE
1|"I do not wish to leave out an important branch of this subject, for it"|FALSE
1|"is a danger from which princes are with difficulty preserved, unless"|FALSE
1|"they are very careful and discriminating. It is that of flatterers, of"|FALSE
1|"whom courts are full, because men are so self-complacent in their own"|FALSE
1|"affairs, and in a way so deceived in them, that they are preserved with"|FALSE
1|"difficulty from this pest, and if they wish to defend themselves they"|FALSE
1|"run the danger of falling into contempt. Because there is no other way"|FALSE
1|"of guarding oneself from flatterers except letting men understand that"|FALSE
1|"to tell you the truth does not offend you; but when every one may tell"|FALSE
1|"you the truth, respect for you abates."|FALSE
1|"Therefore a wise prince ought to hold a third course by choosing the"|FALSE
1|"wise men in his state, and giving to them only the liberty of speaking"|FALSE
1|"the truth to him, and then only of those things of which he inquires,"|FALSE
1|"and of none others; but he ought to question them upon everything, and"|FALSE
1|"listen to their opinions, and afterwards form his own conclusions."|FALSE
1|"With these councillors, separately and collectively, he ought to carry"|FALSE
1|"himself in such a way that each of them should know that, the more"|FALSE
1|"freely he shall speak, the more he shall be preferred; outside of"|FALSE
1|"these, he should listen to no one, pursue the thing resolved on, and be"|FALSE
1|"steadfast in his resolutions. He who does otherwise is either overthrown"|FALSE
1|"by flatterers, or is so often changed by varying opinions that he falls"|FALSE
1|"into contempt."|FALSE
1|"I wish on this subject to adduce a modern example. Fra Luca, the man of"|FALSE
1|"affairs to Maximilian,(*) the present emperor, speaking of his majesty,"|FALSE
1|"said: He consulted with no one, yet never got his own way in anything."|FALSE
1|"This arose because of his following a practice the opposite to the"|FALSE
1|"above; for the emperor is a secretive man--he does not communicate his"|FALSE
1|"designs to any one, nor does he receive opinions on them. But as in"|FALSE
1|"carrying them into effect they become revealed and known, they are"|FALSE
1|"at once obstructed by those men whom he has around him, and he, being"|FALSE
1|"pliant, is diverted from them. Hence it follows that those things he"|FALSE
1|"does one day he undoes the next, and no one ever understands what he"|FALSE
1|"wishes or intends to do, and no one can rely on his resolutions."|FALSE
1|"     (*) Maximilian I, born in 1459, died 1519, Emperor of the"|FALSE
1|"     Holy Roman Empire. He married, first, Mary, daughter of"|FALSE
1|"     Charles the Bold; after her death, Bianca Sforza; and thus"|FALSE
1|"     became involved in Italian politics."|FALSE
1|"A prince, therefore, ought always to take counsel, but only when he"|FALSE
1|"wishes and not when others wish; he ought rather to discourage every one"|FALSE
1|"from offering advice unless he asks it; but, however, he ought to be"|FALSE
1|"a constant inquirer, and afterwards a patient listener concerning the"|FALSE
1|"things of which he inquired; also, on learning that any one, on any"|FALSE
1|"consideration, has not told him the truth, he should let his anger be"|FALSE
1|"felt."|FALSE
1|"And if there are some who think that a prince who conveys an impression"|FALSE
1|"of his wisdom is not so through his own ability, but through the good"|FALSE
1|"advisers that he has around him, beyond doubt they are deceived, because"|FALSE
1|"this is an axiom which never fails: that a prince who is not wise"|FALSE
1|"himself will never take good advice, unless by chance he has yielded his"|FALSE
1|"affairs entirely to one person who happens to be a very prudent man. In"|FALSE
1|"this case indeed he may be well governed, but it would not be for long,"|FALSE
1|"because such a governor would in a short time take away his state from"|FALSE
1|"him."|FALSE
1|"But if a prince who is not inexperienced should take counsel from more"|FALSE
1|"than one he will never get united counsels, nor will he know how to"|FALSE
1|"unite them. Each of the counsellors will think of his own interests, and"|FALSE
1|"the prince will not know how to control them or to see through them. And"|FALSE
1|"they are not to found otherwise, because men will always prove untrue"|FALSE
1|"to you unless they are kept honest by constraint. Therefore it must be"|FALSE
1|"inferred that good counsels, whencesoever they come, are born of"|FALSE
1|"the wisdom of the prince, and not the wisdom of the prince from good"|FALSE
1|"counsels."|FALSE
1|"CHAPTER XXIV -- WHY THE PRINCES OF ITALY HAVE LOST THEIR STATES"|FALSE
1|"The previous suggestions, carefully observed, will enable a new prince"|FALSE
1|"to appear well established, and render him at once more secure and fixed"|FALSE
1|"in the state than if he had been long seated there. For the actions of"|FALSE
1|"a new prince are more narrowly observed than those of an hereditary"|FALSE
1|"one, and when they are seen to be able they gain more men and bind"|FALSE
1|"far tighter than ancient blood; because men are attracted more by the"|FALSE
1|"present than by the past, and when they find the present good they enjoy"|FALSE
1|"it and seek no further; they will also make the utmost defence of a"|FALSE
1|"prince if he fails them not in other things. Thus it will be a double"|FALSE
1|"glory for him to have established a new principality, and adorned and"|FALSE
1|"strengthened it with good laws, good arms, good allies, and with a good"|FALSE
1|"example; so will it be a double disgrace to him who, born a prince,"|FALSE
1|"shall lose his state by want of wisdom."|FALSE
1|"And if those seigniors are considered who have lost their states in"|FALSE
1|"Italy in our times, such as the King of Naples, the Duke of Milan,"|FALSE
1|"and others, there will be found in them, firstly, one common defect in"|FALSE
1|"regard to arms from the causes which have been discussed at length; in"|FALSE
1|"the next place, some one of them will be seen, either to have had the"|FALSE
1|"people hostile, or if he has had the people friendly, he has not known"|FALSE
1|"how to secure the nobles. In the absence of these defects states that"|FALSE
1|"have power enough to keep an army in the field cannot be lost."|FALSE
1|"Philip of Macedon, not the father of Alexander the Great, but he who"|FALSE
1|"was conquered by Titus Quintius, had not much territory compared to"|FALSE
1|"the greatness of the Romans and of Greece who attacked him, yet being a"|FALSE
1|"warlike man who knew how to attract the people and secure the nobles, he"|FALSE
1|"sustained the war against his enemies for many years, and if in the"|FALSE
1|"end he lost the dominion of some cities, nevertheless he retained the"|FALSE
1|"kingdom."|FALSE
1|"Therefore, do not let our princes accuse fortune for the loss of their"|FALSE
1|"principalities after so many years' possession, but rather their own"|FALSE
1|"sloth, because in quiet times they never thought there could be a change"|FALSE
1|"(it is a common defect in man not to make any provision in the calm"|FALSE
1|"against the tempest), and when afterwards the bad times came they"|FALSE
1|"thought of flight and not of defending themselves, and they hoped that"|FALSE
1|"the people, disgusted with the insolence of the conquerors, would recall"|FALSE
1|"them. This course, when others fail, may be good, but it is very bad to"|FALSE
1|"have neglected all other expedients for that, since you would never"|FALSE
1|"wish to fall because you trusted to be able to find someone later on to"|FALSE
1|"restore you. This again either does not happen, or, if it does, it will"|FALSE
1|"not be for your security, because that deliverance is of no avail which"|FALSE
1|"does not depend upon yourself; those only are reliable, certain, and"|FALSE
1|"durable that depend on yourself and your valour."|FALSE
1|"CHAPTER XXV -- WHAT FORTUNE CAN EFFECT IN HUMAN AFFAIRS AND HOW TO"|FALSE
1|"WITHSTAND HER"|FALSE
1|"It is not unknown to me how many men have had, and still have, the"|FALSE
1|"opinion that the affairs of the world are in such wise governed by"|FALSE
1|"fortune and by God that men with their wisdom cannot direct them and"|FALSE
1|"that no one can even help them; and because of this they would have us"|FALSE
1|"believe that it is not necessary to labour much in affairs, but to let"|FALSE
1|"chance govern them. This opinion has been more credited in our times"|FALSE
1|"because of the great changes in affairs which have been seen, and"|FALSE
1|"may still be seen, every day, beyond all human conjecture. Sometimes"|FALSE
1|"pondering over this, I am in some degree inclined to their opinion."|FALSE
1|"Nevertheless, not to extinguish our free will, I hold it to be true that"|FALSE
1|"Fortune is the arbiter of one-half of our actions,(*) but that she still"|FALSE
1|"leaves us to direct the other half, or perhaps a little less."|FALSE
1|"     (*) Frederick the Great was accustomed to say: \"The older"|FALSE
1|"     one gets the more convinced one becomes that his Majesty"|FALSE
1|"     King Chance does three-quarters of the business of this"|FALSE
1|"     miserable universe.\" Sorel's \"Eastern Question.\""|FALSE
1|"I compare her to one of those raging rivers, which when in flood"|FALSE
1|"overflows the plains, sweeping away trees and buildings, bearing away"|FALSE
1|"the soil from place to place; everything flies before it, all yield to"|FALSE
1|"its violence, without being able in any way to withstand it; and yet,"|FALSE
1|"though its nature be such, it does not follow therefore that men, when"|FALSE
1|"the weather becomes fair, shall not make provision, both with defences"|FALSE
1|"and barriers, in such a manner that, rising again, the waters may"|FALSE
1|"pass away by canal, and their force be neither so unrestrained nor so"|FALSE
1|"dangerous. So it happens with fortune, who shows her power where valour"|FALSE
1|"has not prepared to resist her, and thither she turns her forces where"|FALSE
1|"she knows that barriers and defences have not been raised to constrain"|FALSE
1|"her."|FALSE
1|"And if you will consider Italy, which is the seat of these changes, and"|FALSE
1|"which has given to them their impulse, you will see it to be an open"|FALSE
1|"country without barriers and without any defence. For if it had been"|FALSE
1|"defended by proper valour, as are Germany, Spain, and France, either"|FALSE
1|"this invasion would not have made the great changes it has made or it"|FALSE
1|"would not have come at all. And this I consider enough to say concerning"|FALSE
1|"resistance to fortune in general."|FALSE
1|"But confining myself more to the particular, I say that a prince may be"|FALSE
1|"seen happy to-day and ruined to-morrow without having shown any change"|FALSE
1|"of disposition or character. This, I believe, arises firstly from causes"|FALSE
1|"that have already been discussed at length, namely, that the prince who"|FALSE
1|"relies entirely on fortune is lost when it changes. I believe also that"|FALSE
1|"he will be successful who directs his actions according to the spirit of"|FALSE
1|"the times, and that he whose actions do not accord with the times will"|FALSE
1|"not be successful. Because men are seen, in affairs that lead to the end"|FALSE
1|"which every man has before him, namely, glory and riches, to get there"|FALSE
1|"by various methods; one with caution, another with haste; one by force,"|FALSE
1|"another by skill; one by patience, another by its opposite; and each one"|FALSE
