1|"THE LIFE OF CASTRUCCIO CASTRACANI OF LUCCA"|FALSE
1|"WRITTEN BY NICOLO MACHIAVELLI"|FALSE
1|"And sent to his friends ZANOBI BUONDELMONTI And LUIGI ALAMANNI"|FALSE
1|"CASTRUCCIO CASTRACANI 1284-1328"|FALSE
1|"It appears, dearest Zanobi and Luigi, a wonderful thing to those who"|FALSE
1|"have considered the matter, that all men, or the larger number of them,"|FALSE
1|"who have performed great deeds in the world, and excelled all others in"|FALSE
1|"their day, have had their birth and beginning in baseness and obscurity;"|FALSE
1|"or have been aggrieved by Fortune in some outrageous way. They have"|FALSE
1|"either been exposed to the mercy of wild beasts, or they have had so"|FALSE
1|"mean a parentage that in shame they have given themselves out to be"|FALSE
1|"sons of Jove or of some other deity. It would be wearisome to relate who"|FALSE
1|"these persons may have been because they are well known to everybody,"|FALSE
1|"and, as such tales would not be particularly edifying to those who read"|FALSE
1|"them, they are omitted. I believe that these lowly beginnings of great"|FALSE
1|"men occur because Fortune is desirous of showing to the world that such"|FALSE
1|"men owe much to her and little to wisdom, because she begins to show"|FALSE
1|"her hand when wisdom can really take no part in their career: thus all"|FALSE
1|"success must be attributed to her. Castruccio Castracani of Lucca was"|FALSE
1|"one of those men who did great deeds, if he is measured by the times in"|FALSE
1|"which he lived and the city in which he was born; but, like many others,"|FALSE
1|"he was neither fortunate nor distinguished in his birth, as the course"|FALSE
1|"of this history will show. It appeared to be desirable to recall his"|FALSE
1|"memory, because I have discerned in him such indications of valour and"|FALSE
1|"fortune as should make him a great exemplar to men. I think also that"|FALSE
1|"I ought to call your attention to his actions, because you of all men I"|FALSE
1|"know delight most in noble deeds."|FALSE
1|"The family of Castracani was formerly numbered among the noble families"|FALSE
1|"of Lucca, but in the days of which I speak it had somewhat fallen in"|FALSE
1|"estate, as so often happens in this world. To this family was born a son"|FALSE
1|"Antonio, who became a priest of the order of San Michele of Lucca, and"|FALSE
1|"for this reason was honoured with the title of Messer Antonio. He had an"|FALSE
1|"only sister, who had been married to Buonaccorso Cenami, but Buonaccorso"|FALSE
1|"dying she became a widow, and not wishing to marry again went to live"|FALSE
1|"with her brother. Messer Antonio had a vineyard behind the house where"|FALSE
1|"he resided, and as it was bounded on all sides by gardens, any person"|FALSE
1|"could have access to it without difficulty. One morning, shortly after"|FALSE
1|"sunrise, Madonna Dianora, as the sister of Messer Antonio was called,"|FALSE
1|"had occasion to go into the vineyard as usual to gather herbs for"|FALSE
1|"seasoning the dinner, and hearing a slight rustling among the leaves"|FALSE
1|"of a vine she turned her eyes in that direction, and heard something"|FALSE
1|"resembling the cry of an infant. Whereupon she went towards it, and saw"|FALSE
1|"the hands and face of a baby who was lying enveloped in the leaves and"|FALSE
1|"who seemed to be crying for its mother. Partly wondering and partly"|FALSE
1|"fearing, yet full of compassion, she lifted it up and carried it to"|FALSE
1|"the house, where she washed it and clothed it with clean linen as is"|FALSE
1|"customary, and showed it to Messer Antonio when he returned home. When"|FALSE
1|"he heard what had happened and saw the child he was not less surprised"|FALSE
1|"or compassionate than his sister. They discussed between themselves"|FALSE
1|"what should be done, and seeing that he was priest and that she had no"|FALSE
1|"children, they finally determined to bring it up. They had a nurse for"|FALSE
1|"it, and it was reared and loved as if it were their own child. They"|FALSE
1|"baptized it, and gave it the name of Castruccio after their father. As"|FALSE
1|"the years passed Castruccio grew very handsome, and gave evidence of"|FALSE
1|"wit and discretion, and learnt with a quickness beyond his years those"|FALSE
1|"lessons which Messer Antonio imparted to him. Messer Antonio intended"|FALSE
1|"to make a priest of him, and in time would have inducted him into his"|FALSE
1|"canonry and other benefices, and all his instruction was given with"|FALSE
1|"this object; but Antonio discovered that the character of Castruccio was"|FALSE
1|"quite unfitted for the priesthood. As soon as Castruccio reached the"|FALSE
1|"age of fourteen he began to take less notice of the chiding of Messer"|FALSE
1|"Antonio and Madonna Dianora and no longer to fear them; he left"|FALSE
1|"off reading ecclesiastical books, and turned to playing with arms,"|FALSE
1|"delighting in nothing so much as in learning their uses, and in running,"|FALSE
1|"leaping, and wrestling with other boys. In all exercises he far excelled"|FALSE
1|"his companions in courage and bodily strength, and if at any time he did"|FALSE
1|"turn to books, only those pleased him which told of wars and the mighty"|FALSE
1|"deeds of men. Messer Antonio beheld all this with vexation and sorrow."|FALSE
1|"There lived in the city of Lucca a gentleman of the Guinigi family,"|FALSE
1|"named Messer Francesco, whose profession was arms and who in riches,"|FALSE
1|"bodily strength, and valour excelled all other men in Lucca. He had"|FALSE
1|"often fought under the command of the Visconti of Milan, and as a"|FALSE
1|"Ghibelline was the valued leader of that party in Lucca. This gentleman"|FALSE
1|"resided in Lucca and was accustomed to assemble with others most"|FALSE
1|"mornings and evenings under the balcony of the Podesta, which is at the"|FALSE
1|"top of the square of San Michele, the finest square in Lucca, and he had"|FALSE
1|"often seen Castruccio taking part with other children of the street"|FALSE
1|"in those games of which I have spoken. Noticing that Castruccio far"|FALSE
1|"excelled the other boys, and that he appeared to exercise a royal"|FALSE
1|"authority over them, and that they loved and obeyed him, Messer"|FALSE
1|"Francesco became greatly desirous of learning who he was. Being informed"|FALSE
1|"of the circumstances of the bringing up of Castruccio he felt a greater"|FALSE
1|"desire to have him near to him. Therefore he called him one day and"|FALSE
1|"asked him whether he would more willingly live in the house of a"|FALSE
1|"gentleman, where he would learn to ride horses and use arms, or in"|FALSE
1|"the house of a priest, where he would learn nothing but masses and"|FALSE
1|"the services of the Church. Messer Francesco could see that it pleased"|FALSE
1|"Castruccio greatly to hear horses and arms spoken of, even though"|FALSE
1|"he stood silent, blushing modestly; but being encouraged by Messer"|FALSE
1|"Francesco to speak, he answered that, if his master were agreeable,"|FALSE
1|"nothing would please him more than to give up his priestly studies and"|FALSE
1|"take up those of a soldier. This reply delighted Messer Francesco, and"|FALSE
1|"in a very short time he obtained the consent of Messer Antonio, who was"|FALSE
1|"driven to yield by his knowledge of the nature of the lad, and the fear"|FALSE
1|"that he would not be able to hold him much longer."|FALSE
1|"Thus Castruccio passed from the house of Messer Antonio the priest"|FALSE
1|"to the house of Messer Francesco Guinigi the soldier, and it was"|FALSE
1|"astonishing to find that in a very short time he manifested all that"|FALSE
1|"virtue and bearing which we are accustomed to associate with a true"|FALSE
1|"gentleman. In the first place he became an accomplished horseman, and"|FALSE
1|"could manage with ease the most fiery charger, and in all jousts and"|FALSE
1|"tournaments, although still a youth, he was observed beyond all others,"|FALSE
1|"and he excelled in all exercises of strength and dexterity. But what"|FALSE
1|"enhanced so much the charm of these accomplishments, was the delightful"|FALSE
1|"modesty which enabled him to avoid offence in either act or word to"|FALSE
1|"others, for he was deferential to the great men, modest with his equals,"|FALSE
1|"and courteous to his inferiors. These gifts made him beloved, not only"|FALSE
1|"by all the Guinigi family, but by all Lucca. When Castruccio had reached"|FALSE
1|"his eighteenth year, the Ghibellines were driven from Pavia by the"|FALSE
1|"Guelphs, and Messer Francesco was sent by the Visconti to assist the"|FALSE
1|"Ghibellines, and with him went Castruccio, in charge of his forces."|FALSE
1|"Castruccio gave ample proof of his prudence and courage in this"|FALSE
1|"expedition, acquiring greater reputation than any other captain, and"|FALSE
1|"his name and fame were known, not only in Pavia, but throughout all"|FALSE
1|"Lombardy."|FALSE
1|"Castruccio, having returned to Lucca in far higher estimation that he"|FALSE
1|"left it, did not omit to use all the means in his power to gain as many"|FALSE
1|"friends as he could, neglecting none of those arts which are necessary"|FALSE
1|"for that purpose. About this time Messer Francesco died, leaving a son"|FALSE
1|"thirteen years of age named Pagolo, and having appointed Castruccio"|FALSE
