1|"knowest how to use it with prudence, will assist thee to come to terms"|FALSE
1|"with the Florentines, who, as they are suffering under this great"|FALSE
1|"defeat, should be inclined to listen to thee. And whereas I have sought"|FALSE
1|"to make them my enemies, because I believed that war with them would"|FALSE
1|"conduce to my power and glory, thou hast every inducement to make"|FALSE
1|"friends of them, because their alliance will bring thee advantages"|FALSE
1|"and security. It is of the greatest important in this world that a man"|FALSE
1|"should know himself, and the measure of his own strength and means; and"|FALSE
1|"he who knows that he has not a genius for fighting must learn how to"|FALSE
1|"govern by the arts of peace. And it will be well for thee to rule"|FALSE
1|"they conduct by my counsel, and to learn in this way to enjoy what my"|FALSE
1|"life-work and dangers have gained; and in this thou wilt easily succeed"|FALSE
1|"when thou hast learnt to believe that what I have told thee is true. And"|FALSE
1|"thou wilt be doubly indebted to me, in that I have left thee this realm"|FALSE
1|"and have taught thee how to keep it.\""|FALSE
1|"After this there came to Castruccio those citizens of Pisa, Pistoia, and"|FALSE
1|"Lucca, who had been fighting at his side, and whilst recommending Pagolo"|FALSE
1|"to them, and making them swear obedience to him as his successor, he"|FALSE
1|"died. He left a happy memory to those who had known him, and no"|FALSE
1|"prince of those times was ever loved with such devotion as he was. His"|FALSE
1|"obsequies were celebrated with every sign of mourning, and he was buried"|FALSE
1|"in San Francesco at Lucca. Fortune was not so friendly to Pagolo Guinigi"|FALSE
1|"as she had been to Castruccio, for he had not the abilities. Not long"|FALSE
1|"after the death of Castruccio, Pagolo lost Pisa, and then Pistoia, and"|FALSE
1|"only with difficulty held on to Lucca. This latter city continued in the"|FALSE
1|"family of Guinigi until the time of the great-grandson of Pagolo."|FALSE
1|"From what has been related here it will be seen that Castruccio was a"|FALSE
1|"man of exceptional abilities, not only measured by men of his own"|FALSE
1|"time, but also by those of an earlier date. In stature he was above"|FALSE
1|"the ordinary height, and perfectly proportioned. He was of a gracious"|FALSE
1|"presence, and he welcomed men with such urbanity that those who spoke"|FALSE
1|"with him rarely left him displeased. His hair was inclined to be red,"|FALSE
1|"and he wore it cut short above the ears, and, whether it rained or"|FALSE
1|"snowed, he always went without a hat. He was delightful among friends,"|FALSE
1|"but terrible to his enemies; just to his subjects; ready to play false"|FALSE
1|"with the unfaithful, and willing to overcome by fraud those whom he"|FALSE
1|"desired to subdue, because he was wont to say that it was the victory"|FALSE
1|"that brought the glory, not the methods of achieving it. No one was"|FALSE
1|"bolder in facing danger, none more prudent in extricating himself. He"|FALSE
1|"was accustomed to say that men ought to attempt everything and fear"|FALSE
1|"nothing; that God is a lover of strong men, because one always sees that"|FALSE
1|"the weak are chastised by the strong. He was also wonderfully sharp or"|FALSE
1|"biting though courteous in his answers; and as he did not look for any"|FALSE
1|"indulgence in this way of speaking from others, so he was not angered"|FALSE
1|"with others did not show it to him. It has often happened that he has"|FALSE
1|"listened quietly when others have spoken sharply to him, as on the"|FALSE
1|"following occasions. He had caused a ducat to be given for a partridge,"|FALSE
1|"and was taken to task for doing so by a friend, to whom Castruccio had"|FALSE
1|"said: \"You would not have given more than a penny.\" \"That is true,\""|FALSE
1|"answered the friend. Then said Castruccio to him: \"A ducat is much less"|FALSE
1|"to me.\" Having about him a flatterer on whom he had spat to show that"|FALSE
1|"he scorned him, the flatterer said to him: \"Fisherman are willing to let"|FALSE
1|"the waters of the sea saturate them in order that they make take a few"|FALSE
1|"little fishes, and I allow myself to be wetted by spittle that I may"|FALSE
1|"catch a whale\"; and this was not only heard by Castruccio with patience"|FALSE
1|"but rewarded. When told by a priest that it was wicked for him to live"|FALSE
1|"so sumptuously, Castruccio said: \"If that be a vice than you should"|FALSE
1|"not fare so splendidly at the feasts of our saints.\" Passing through a"|FALSE
1|"street he saw a young man as he came out of a house of ill fame blush at"|FALSE
1|"being seen by Castruccio, and said to him: \"Thou shouldst not be ashamed"|FALSE
1|"when thou comest out, but when thou goest into such places.\" A friend"|FALSE
1|"gave him a very curiously tied knot to undo and was told: \"Fool, do"|FALSE
1|"you think that I wish to untie a thing which gave so much trouble to"|FALSE
1|"fasten.\" Castruccio said to one who professed to be a philosopher: \"You"|FALSE
1|"are like the dogs who always run after those who will give them the best"|FALSE
1|"to eat,\" and was answered: \"We are rather like the doctors who go to the"|FALSE
1|"houses of those who have the greatest need of them.\" Going by water from"|FALSE
1|"Pisa to Leghorn, Castruccio was much disturbed by a dangerous storm that"|FALSE
1|"sprang up, and was reproached for cowardice by one of those with him,"|FALSE
1|"who said that he did not fear anything. Castruccio answered that he"|FALSE
1|"did not wonder at that, since every man valued his soul for what is was"|FALSE
1|"worth. Being asked by one what he ought to do to gain estimation, he"|FALSE
1|"said: \"When thou goest to a banquet take care that thou dost not seat"|FALSE
1|"one piece of wood upon another.\" To a person who was boasting that he"|FALSE
1|"had read many things, Castruccio said: \"He knows better than to boast"|FALSE
1|"of remembering many things.\" Someone bragged that he could drink much"|FALSE
1|"without becoming intoxicated. Castruccio replied: \"An ox does the"|FALSE
1|"same.\" Castruccio was acquainted with a girl with whom he had intimate"|FALSE
1|"relations, and being blamed by a friend who told him that it was"|FALSE
1|"undignified for him to be taken in by a woman, he said: \"She has not"|FALSE
1|"taken me in, I have taken her.\" Being also blamed for eating very dainty"|FALSE
1|"foods, he answered: \"Thou dost not spend as much as I do?\" and being"|FALSE
1|"told that it was true, he continued: \"Then thou art more avaricious"|FALSE
1|"than I am gluttonous.\" Being invited by Taddeo Bernardi, a very rich and"|FALSE
1|"splendid citizen of Luca, to supper, he went to the house and was shown"|FALSE
1|"by Taddeo into a chamber hung with silk and paved with fine stones"|FALSE
1|"representing flowers and foliage of the most beautiful colouring."|FALSE
1|"Castruccio gathered some saliva in his mouth and spat it out upon"|FALSE
1|"Taddeo, and seeing him much disturbed by this, said to him: \"I knew not"|FALSE
1|"where to spit in order to offend thee less.\" Being asked how Caesar"|FALSE
1|"died he said: \"God willing I will die as he did.\" Being one night in the"|FALSE
1|"house of one of his gentlemen where many ladies were assembled, he was"|FALSE
1|"reproved by one of his friends for dancing and amusing himself with"|FALSE
1|"them more than was usual in one of his station, so he said: \"He who is"|FALSE
1|"considered wise by day will not be considered a fool at night.\" A person"|FALSE
1|"came to demand a favour of Castruccio, and thinking he was not listening"|FALSE
1|"to his plea threw himself on his knees to the ground, and being sharply"|FALSE
1|"reproved by Castruccio, said: \"Thou art the reason of my acting thus for"|FALSE
1|"thou hast thy ears in thy feet,\" whereupon he obtained double the favour"|FALSE
1|"he had asked. Castruccio used to say that the way to hell was an easy"|FALSE
1|"one, seeing that it was in a downward direction and you travelled"|FALSE
1|"blindfolded. Being asked a favour by one who used many superfluous"|FALSE
1|"words, he said to him: \"When you have another request to make, send"|FALSE
1|"someone else to make it.\" Having been wearied by a similar man with a"|FALSE
1|"long oration who wound up by saying: \"Perhaps I have fatigued you by"|FALSE
1|"speaking so long,\" Castruccio said: \"You have not, because I have not"|FALSE
1|"listened to a word you said.\" He used to say of one who had been a"|FALSE
1|"beautiful child and who afterwards became a fine man, that he was"|FALSE
1|"dangerous, because he first took the husbands from the wives and now he"|FALSE
1|"took the wives from their husbands. To an envious man who laughed, he"|FALSE
1|"said: \"Do you laugh because you are successful or because another is"|FALSE
1|"unfortunate?\" Whilst he was still in the charge of Messer Francesco"|FALSE
1|"Guinigi, one of his companions said to him: \"What shall I give you if"|FALSE
1|"you will let me give you a blow on the nose?\" Castruccio answered:"|FALSE
1|"\"A helmet.\" Having put to death a citizen of Lucca who had been"|FALSE
1|"instrumental in raising him to power, and being told that he had done"|FALSE
1|"wrong to kill one of his old friends, he answered that people deceived"|FALSE
1|"themselves; he had only killed a new enemy. Castruccio praised greatly"|FALSE
1|"those men who intended to take a wife and then did not do so, saying"|FALSE
1|"that they were like men who said they would go to sea, and then refused"|FALSE
1|"when the time came. He said that it always struck him with surprise that"|FALSE
1|"whilst men in buying an earthen or glass vase would sound it first to"|FALSE
1|"learn if it were good, yet in choosing a wife they were content with"|FALSE
1|"only looking at her. He was once asked in what manner he would wish to"|FALSE
1|"be buried when he died, and answered: \"With the face turned downwards,"|FALSE
1|"for I know when I am gone this country will be turned upside down.\" On"|FALSE
1|"being asked if it had ever occurred to him to become a friar in order to"|FALSE
1|"save his soul, he answered that it had not, because it appeared strange"|FALSE
1|"to him that Fra Lazerone should go to Paradise and Uguccione della"|FALSE
1|"Faggiuola to the Inferno. He was once asked when should a man eat to"|FALSE
1|"preserve his health, and replied: \"If the man be rich let him eat"|FALSE
1|"when he is hungry; if he be poor, then when he can.\" Seeing on of his"|FALSE
1|"gentlemen make a member of his family lace him up, he said to him: \"I"|FALSE
1|"pray God that you will let him feed you also.\" Seeing that someone had"|FALSE
1|"written upon his house in Latin the words: \"May God preserve this house"|FALSE
1|"from the wicked,\" he said, \"The owner must never go in.\" Passing through"|FALSE
1|"one of the streets he saw a small house with a very large door, and"|FALSE
1|"remarked: \"That house will fly through the door.\" He was having a"|FALSE
1|"discussion with the ambassador of the King of Naples concerning the"|FALSE
1|"property of some banished nobles, when a dispute arose between them, and"|FALSE
1|"the ambassador asked him if he had no fear of the king. \"Is this king of"|FALSE
1|"yours a bad man or a good one?\" asked Castruccio, and was told that he"|FALSE
1|"was a good one, whereupon he said, \"Why should you suggest that I should"|FALSE
1|"be afraid of a good man?\""|FALSE
1|"I could recount many other stories of his sayings both witty and"|FALSE
1|"weighty, but I think that the above will be sufficient testimony to"|FALSE
1|"his high qualities. He lived forty-four years, and was in every way a"|FALSE
1|"prince. And as he was surrounded by many evidences of his good fortune,"|FALSE
1|"so he also desired to have near him some memorials of his bad fortune;"|FALSE
1|"therefore the manacles with which he was chained in prison are to be"|FALSE
1|"seen to this day fixed up in the tower of his residence, where they were"|FALSE
1|"placed by him to testify for ever to his days of adversity. As in"|FALSE
1|"his life he was inferior neither to Philip of Macedon, the father of"|FALSE
1|"Alexander, nor to Scipio of Rome, so he died in the same year of his"|FALSE
1|"age as they did, and he would doubtless have excelled both of them had"|FALSE
1|"Fortune decreed that he should be born, not in Lucca, but in Macedonia"|FALSE
1|"or Rome."|FALSE
